{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Idaho", "text_new": "{{Short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Idaho}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Idaho\n| map1            = File:COVID-19_in_Idaho.png\n| places          = \n| legend1         = {{Center|Map of counties in Idaho with confirmed cases (as of March 30):}}\n{{Block indent|\n{{legend|#ffffff| 0 confirmed cases reported}}\n{{legend|#fee5d9|<5 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fcbba1|5-10 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fc9272|11-20 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#fb6a4a|21-50 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#de2d26|51-100 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#a50f15|>100 confirmed cases}}|left = 3}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Idaho]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Ada County, Idaho|Ada County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 13, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})<ref name=\"idaho-firstcase\">{{cite web |title=First case of novel coronavirus in Idaho has been confirmed |url=https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/AboutUs/Newsroom/tabid/130/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/2087/First-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-Idaho-has-been-confirmed.aspx |website=Idaho Department of Health and Welfare |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Joint news release with Idaho Department of Health and Welfare |url=https://cdhd.idaho.gov/pdfs/cd/Coronavirus/IDHW-CDH%20First%20Confirmed%20case%20of%20COVID-19%203-13-20.pdf |website=Idaho Central District Health |accessdate=24 March 2020 }}</ref>\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 1,453\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 33\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.idaho.gov/}}\n| hospitalized_cases = 135\n| critical_cases  = 38\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Idaho''' is part of the ongoing [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19)]]. The first case of COVID-19 in [[Idaho]] was confirmed on March 13, 2020, when a [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]] woman tested positive.<ref name=\"idaho-firstcase\" />  She recently had attended a conference in [[New York City]] where officials confirmed that three other attendees previously tested positive with the coronavirus infection. As of April 15, there were 1,587 confirmed cases and 41 deaths within Idaho.<ref name=\"COVID-19 in Idaho\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 in Idaho |url=https://coronavirus.idaho.gov |website=Idaho - Official Resources for the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Idaho medical cases chart}}\n\n===March===\nOn March 13, 2020, officials from the [https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/ Idaho Department of Health and Welfare] announced the first confirmed case of the novel coronavirus COVID-19 within the state of Idaho.<ref name=\"idaho-firstcase\" />  A woman over the age of 50 from the southwestern part of the state was confirmed to have the coronavirus infection.  She contracted the infection while attending a conference in [[New York City]].  Conference coordinators notified attendees that three individuals previously tested positive for the coronavirus.  The Idahoan did not require hospitalization and was recovering from mild symptoms from her home.  At the time of the announcement, there were 1,629 total cases and 41 deaths in the United States.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 14, state officials announced the second confirmed case within the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=First case of novel coronavirus reported in south-central Idaho; the second in the state |url=https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/AboutUs/Newsroom/tabid/130/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/2088/UPDATE-CONTACT-FOR-PHD-First-case-of-novel-coronavirus-reported-in-south-central-Idaho-the-second-in-the-state.aspx |website=Idaho Department of Health and Welfare |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The [https://phd5.idaho.gov/# South Central Public Health District], announced that a woman over the age of 50 that resides in [[Blaine County, Idaho|Blaine County]] had contracted the infection.<ref name=\"idhw-3cases\" />  Like the first case, she did not require hospitalization and she was recovering from mild symptoms from home. Later on in the day, three additional confirmed cases of COVID-19 were reported in the state by three of the seven health districts in the state which brought the confirmed total cases of coronavirus to five in Idaho.<ref name=\"idhw-3cases\">{{cite web |title=Idaho reports three additional cases of COVID-19 in the state, for a total of 5 |url=https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/AboutUs/Newsroom/tabid/130/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/2089/Idaho-reports-three-additional-cases-of-COVID19-in-the-state-for-a-total-of-5.aspx |website=Idaho Department of Health and Welfare |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>  Officials from Central District Health announced their second confirmed case which was a male from [[Ada County, Idaho|Ada County]] in his 50s. He was not hospitalized and was recovering at home.  South Central Public Health reported their second confirmed case in a female that is over the age of 70 who was hospitalized.<ref name=\"idhw-3cases\" /> Eastern Idaho Public Health reported a confirmed positive case in a woman under the age of 60 who resides in [[Teton County, Idaho|Teton County]]. She had contracted the coronavirus from contact with a confirmed case in a neighboring state; she was not hospitalized.<ref name=\"idhw-3cases\" /> The South Central Public Health District, announced that a woman over the age of 50 that resides in [[Blaine County, Idaho|Blaine County]] had contracted the infection.<ref name=\"idhw-3cases\" />  Like the first case, she did not require hospitalization and she was recovering from mild symptoms from home.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 17, two more confirmed cases of the infection were reported bringing the total to seven.<ref>{{cite web |title=Idaho reports two more cases of COVID-19 for a total of seven in the state |url=https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/AboutUs/Newsroom/tabid/130/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/2090/Idaho-reports-two-more-cases-of-COVID19-for-a-total-of-seven-in-the-state.aspx |website=IDHW |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The first case on this date was by officials from Central District Health reported that a female under the age of 50 in Ada County was recovering at home and was not hospitalized. The second confirmed case was a female over the age of 50 as reported by South Central Public Health officials.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 18, two additional confirmed cases were announced by South Central Public Health District officials. One is a male from Blaine County in his 40s and the other a male in his 80s from [[Twin Falls County, Idaho|Twin Falls County]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Two more cases of novel coronavirus reported in south-central Idaho, including the first case in Twin Falls County |url=https://www.phd5.idaho.gov/Documents/Press-Releases/2020/3-18-2020_Coronavirus_fifthcaseSCPHD.pdf |website=South Central Public Health District |accessdate=24 March 2020 }}</ref> These cases were the first known [[Transmission (medicine)|community spread]] transmission of the coronavirus in South Central Idaho.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 26, state officials confirmed the first three deaths in the state. Two were males in Blaine County and one was a male in Canyon County.<ref>{{cite web |title=Idaho reports three deaths related to COVID-19 |url= https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/AboutUs/Newsroom/tabid/130/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/2095/Idaho-reports-3-deaths-related-to-COVID19.aspx |website=Idaho Department of Health and Welfare |accessdate=30 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 13, 2020, the same day as when the first confirmed case of the coronavirus in Idaho was announced, Governor [[Brad Little]] stated \"We have been preparing for this since January when the first confirmed case of coronavirus was confirmed in the United States, we have taken many proactive steps, and we are in a good position to respond. Our focus is on slowing the spread of coronavirus to protect vulnerable individuals and preserve capacity in our healthcare facilities.\"<ref name=\"idaho-firstcase\" /> The Governor also signed a proactive emergency declaration to enable the Idaho Emergency Operations Plan along with making funds available for use in the Idaho Emergency Disaster Fund.<ref>{{cite web |title=Governor signs proactive emergency declaration to further prevent coronavirus spread in Idaho |url=https://gov.idaho.gov/pressrelease/governor-signs-proactive-emergency-declaration-to-further-prevent-coronavirus-spread-in-idaho/ |website=Office of the Governor of Idaho |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Idaho Emergency Proclamation |url=https://coronavirus.idaho.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/127/2020/03/proclamation_emergency-declaration_031320.pdf |website=Office of the Governor of Idaho |accessdate=24 March 2020 }}</ref> This declaration allows for the  flexibility to expedite contracts and purchasing of supplies, aids with obtaining critical supplies from the [[Strategic National Stockpile|national stockpile]] along with adding provisions to expedite renewals of state nursing licenses for those who have retired or left the profession.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 17, Idaho Department of Health and Welfare's Division of Welfare announced that on March 18 they would stop walk-in services in some of their locations and move to appointment and phone-based services.<ref>{{cite web |title=To minimize COVID-19 risk, Division of Welfare offices open for appointments only |url=https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/AboutUs/Newsroom/tabid/130/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/2091/To-minimize-COVID19-risk-Division-of-Welfare-offices-open-for-appointments-only.aspx |website=IDHM |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Those locations are [[Boise, Idaho|Boise (Westgate)]], [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d\u2019Alene]], [[Idaho Falls]], [[Lewiston, Idaho|Lewiston]], [[Nampa, Idaho|Nampa]], [[Payette, Idaho|Payette]], [[Pocatello, Idaho|Pocatello]], [[Preston, Idaho|Preston]], and [[Twin Falls, Idaho|Twin Falls]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 22, Idaho Department of Health and Welfare addressed how COVID-19 cases were counted in the state.<ref>{{cite web |title=How COVID-19 cases are counted |url=https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/AboutUs/Newsroom/tabid/130/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/2093/How-COVID19-cases-are-counted.aspx |website=IDHW |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The state counts were based on records that are submitted through Idaho's statewide disease tracking system and don't count the cases by the local public health departments that have not been determined thought investigations or been submitted to the state. By doing so, the count is that of Idaho residents and not those who might reside in another are outside of the state.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn March 23, the Governor Little signed two proclamations with the first \"one lifting restrictions in 125 administrative rules to increase healthcare provider capacity and reduce barriers to healthcare access\" and the second to extend the state income tax filing and payment deadlines to June 15 for all citizens and businesses in Idaho.<ref>{{cite web |title=Governor Little rolls out latest actions to further prepare Idaho for coronavirus, ease burdens on citizens |url=https://gov.idaho.gov/pressrelease/governor-little-rolls-out-latest-actions-to-further-prepare-idaho-for-coronavirus-ease-burdens-on-citizens/ |website=Office of the Governor of Idaho |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Governor Little issued a statewide [[stay-at-home order]] for residents to stay and work from home as much as possible. The order also closed non-essential businesses and banned non-essential gatherings effective on the same day for at least 21 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kloppenburg |first1=Katie |title=Governor Little issues stay-at-home order for Idaho |url=https://www.kivitv.com/news/governor-little-issues-stay-at-home-order-for-idaho |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=KIVI |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Some citizens and officials are challenging the social distancing rules.<ref name=\"Baker2020\">{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Mike |title=A \u2018Liberty\u2019 Rebellion in Idaho Threatens to Undermine Coronavirus Orders |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/coronavirus-idaho-bundy-patriot.html?searchResultPosition=1 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, Governor Little extended the stay-home order through \"at least\" April 30, even as protests continued.\n<ref name=\"IdahoStayAtHomeExt\">{{cite news|title=Idaho governor extends coronavirus closures, stay-home order through end of April|first=Katie|last=Terhune|publisher=[[KTVB]]|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/little-extends-stay-at-home-order-idaho-coronavirus-april-30/277-1a4f8090-5d36-4168-b9e5-75edd3577b92}}</ref>\nThe amended order further directs residents to wear masks in public, and\nalso mandates that travelers from outside the state self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival.  It also loosens business closures, allowing some \"non-essential\" businesses to reopen if they are able to restrict operation to delivery and curbside pickup.\n\n==Statistics==\n<!-- DO NOT update without official confirmation from Idaho Department of Health and Welfare -->\n<!-- All Counties are added to the table so you will need unhide if county does not show once published -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) cases in Idaho<ref name=\"COVID-19 in Idaho\"/>\nUpdated April 13, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Cases\n! scope=\"col\" |per 100,000\n! scope=\"col\" |Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ada County, Idaho|Ada]]\n|529\n|113\n|9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Adams County, Idaho|Adams]]\n|1\n|24\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bannock County, Idaho|Bannock]]\n|5\n|6\n|0\n|-\n<!--\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bear Lake County, Idaho|Bear Lake]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n|-\n<!--\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Benewah County, Idaho|Benewah]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bingham County, Idaho|Bingham]]\n|2\n|4\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Blaine County, Idaho|Blaine]]\n|458\n|2,026\n|5\n|-\n<!--\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Boise County, Idaho|Boise]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bonner County, Idaho|Bonner]]\n|4\n|9\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bonneville County, Idaho|Bonneville]]\n|14\n|12\n|0\n|-\n<!--\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Boundary County, Idaho|Boundary]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n|-\n<!--\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Butte County, Idaho|Butte]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Camas County, Idaho|Camas]]\n|1\n|89\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Canyon County, Idaho|Canyon]]\n|161\n|72\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Caribou County, Idaho|Caribou]]\n|1\n|14\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cassia County, Idaho|Cassia]]\n|9\n|38\n|1\n|-\n<!--\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clark County, Idaho|Clark]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n|-\n<!--\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clearwater County, Idaho|Clearwater]]\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Custer County, Idaho|Custer]]\n|2\n|48\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:lef