{"title_page": "McMillan Magnet Center", "text_new": "{{Infobox School\n| name = McMillan Magnet Center\n| type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]], [[Magnet school|magnet]] [[middle school]]\n| location = 3802 Redick Avenue<br/>Omaha, Nebraska 68112 <br />United States\n| image =\n| district = [[Omaha Public Schools]]\n| grades = [[sixth grade|6]]-[[eighth grade|8]]\n| principal = Dr. Monica Green<ref name=\"ops-mcmillan\">[http://www.ops.org/middle/MCMILLAN/] - [http://www.ops.org/middle/mcmillan/STAFF/AdministrativeTeam/tabid/504/Default.aspx]</ref>\n| faculty = \n| students = \n| colors = {{Color box|blue|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|gold|border=darkgray}} Blue and gold\n| mascot = Monarch (lion)\n| motto = \n| free_label = \n| free_label2 = \n| free_text = \n| free_text2 = \n| website = http://www.ops.org/middle/mcmillan/\n| coordinates = {{Coord|41|19|06|N|95|58|14|W|format=dms|display=inline, title|type:edu_region:US-NE}}\n}}\n'''McMillan Magnet School''', formerly known as '''McMillan Junior High School''', is a middle school located at 3802 Redick Avenue in [[North Omaha, Nebraska]], United States. McMillan is a [[magnet school]], focusing on technology, mathematics, engineering, and communication arts.\n\n==History==\nMcMillan opened in 1958, and its students soon chose the Monarch (Lion) as the school mascot. Named for Edward E. McMillan (1875\u20131943), the first principal of North High School, McMillan became [[Omaha Public Schools]]' first magnet junior high school in the 1980s. Originally a school for [[seventh grade|seventh]], [[eighth grade|eighth]] and [[ninth grade]] students, in 1989 ninth graders were permanently moved to [[List of public schools in Omaha, Nebraska#High schools|high schools]] throughout the city.<ref>[http://www.ops.org/middle/mcmillan/HOME/SchoolHistory/tabid/59/Default.aspx \"History of McMillan Magnet Center\"]. Omaha Public Schools. Retrieved 9/9/07.</ref>\n\n==Features==\nAs a magnet school, McMillan features special courses in computers and mathematics. \n\nThe name of the school was changed to McMillan Magnet Center in the late 1990s. \n\nThe school completed a $13 million renovation project in 2003, including a library/media center, technology and living laboratories, computer labs, and an indoor and outdoor athletic complex. McMillan also offers a program for [[gifted student|gifted and talented students]].<ref>[http://www2.ops.org/gifted/pdf/mcmillanbrochure.pdf \"McMillan Magnet Center: Programs and Opportunities for Gifted and Talented Learners\"]. Omaha Public Schools. Retrieved 9/9/07.</ref>\n\n==Trivia==\nIn 1959 richard erickson (16) suffered a head injury from slipping and falling beside McMillan's pool.\n\nIn the 60s a kid was thrown out of the window cause of racial reasons.\n\nIn 1967 McMillan had a Fire that was 'Not Accidental' cause by a nine year old boy. Also in 1967 on December 15th a boy was shot in the eye with bleach from a hypodermic syringe in the locker room.  Intrestingly the school  Did not  notify anyone else when they could not reach his mom by phone\n\nIn (date unknown) McMillan had a tar leak coming from the roof.\n\nThe architects and engineers for McMillan was leo a. daly co.\n\nCheryl Tschetter worked at McMillan for 40 years (1975-2014) and 4 decades. \n\nMyrton hall was the first principal of McMillan. He died on Feb 21st 2017 from complications of a fall. He was  95.\n\nRespected teacher and swim coach of the boys swim team Tom Gellatly was arrested with two counts of possessing child pornography.\n\nScience teacher Patrick Koscis was fired for letting students fight outside\n\nDespite having cancer teacher Susan M. Roberts never quit teaching. she died on Nov 22, 2010 and was born on Nov 21, 1954.\n\nThree students were expelled because of  ba sexually assaulting a student \n\nOn febuary 12 2020 police were called cause of a potential threat luckily no threat was found.\n\nStudent Porcha Busch was expelled cause of a fight with another student during which Busch accidentally struck and injured an assistant principal who was attempting to restrain Busch and break up the fight\n\nNov 21, 2017 police, and fire officials responded to a call to investigate a fire.\n\nA teacher once had a book thrown to her head.\n\nA student one got shot in the parking lot \n\nA student once brought a gun to McMillan\n\nBefore security student's used to smoke at 'smoker's corner' located outside the end of the east wing.\n\nIn 2001, during basketball tryouts a student named harley collins fell the to the ground, when at hospital he died of an unknown heart disease.\n\nSometime before 2001 (either in the 70s 80s or 90s) a student that went there also died.\n\nIn 2018 my brother's friend who also went to mcmillan hung himself at his home and died. it wasnt until some time later that my brother started hearing and seeing things at mcmillan. Also in 2018 another student who went to mcmillan named reese died while taking a nap at home. Reese's mother was in the morning announcments the next day crying, it was hard understanding her.\n\nParanormal has been seen and heard at McMillan. the people who witnessed it was Me, a security gaurd and my journalism teacher. some other teachers beleive McMillan is haunted also.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Grandgenett, N. (1995) [http://eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/contentdelivery/servlet/ERICServlet?accno=ED392398 \"McMillan Magnet School: A Case History of a School Acquiring a Critical Mass of Computer Technology and Internet Connectivity.\"] Mid-Continent Regional Educational Laboratory.\n\n{{North Omaha}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in North Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Middle schools in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Public middle schools in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Magnet schools in Nebraska]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox School\n| name = McMillan Magnet Center\n| type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]], [[Magnet school|magnet]] [[middle school]]\n| location = 3802 Redick Avenue<br/>Omaha, Nebraska 68112 <br />United States\n| image =\n| district = [[Omaha Public Schools]]\n| grades = [[sixth grade|6]]-[[eighth grade|8]]\n| principal = Dr. Monica Green<ref name=\"ops-mcmillan\">[http://www.ops.org/middle/MCMILLAN/] - [http://www.ops.org/middle/mcmillan/STAFF/AdministrativeTeam/tabid/504/Default.aspx]</ref>\n| faculty = \n| students = \n| colors = {{Color box|blue|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|gold|border=darkgray}} Blue and gold\n| mascot = Monarch (lion)\n| motto = \n| free_label = \n| free_label2 = \n| free_text = \n| free_text2 = \n| website = http://www.ops.org/middle/mcmillan/\n| coordinates = {{Coord|41|19|06|N|95|58|14|W|format=dms|display=inline, title|type:edu_region:US-NE}}\n}}\n'''McMillan Magnet School''', formerly known as '''McMillan Junior High School''', is a middle school located at 3802 Redick Avenue in [[North Omaha, Nebraska]], United States. McMillan is a [[magnet school]], focusing on technology, mathematics, engineering, and communication arts.\n\n==History==\nMcMillan opened in 1958, and its students soon chose the Monarch (Lion) as the school mascot. Named for Edward E. McMillan (1875\u20131943), the first principal of North High School, McMillan became [[Omaha Public Schools]]' first magnet junior high school in the 1980s. Originally a school for [[seventh grade|seventh]], [[eighth grade|eighth]] and [[ninth grade]] students, in 1989 ninth graders were permanently moved to [[List of public schools in Omaha, Nebraska#High schools|high schools]] throughout the city.<ref>[http://www.ops.org/middle/mcmillan/HOME/SchoolHistory/tabid/59/Default.aspx \"History of McMillan Magnet Center\"]. Omaha Public Schools. Retrieved 9/9/07.</ref>\n\n==Features==\nAs a magnet school, McMillan features special courses in computers and mathematics. \n\nThe name of the school was changed to McMillan Magnet Center in the late 1990s. \n\nThe school completed a $13 million renovation project in 2003, including a library/media center, technology and living laboratories, computer labs, and an indoor and outdoor athletic complex. McMillan also offers a program for [[gifted student|gifted and talented students]].<ref>[http://www2.ops.org/gifted/pdf/mcmillanbrochure.pdf \"McMillan Magnet Center: Programs and Opportunities for Gifted and Talented Learners\"]. Omaha Public Schools. Retrieved 9/9/07.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public schools in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Grandgenett, N. (1995) [http://eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/contentdelivery/servlet/ERICServlet?accno=ED392398 \"McMillan Magnet School: A Case History of a School Acquiring a Critical Mass of Computer Technology and Internet Connectivity.\"] Mid-Continent Regional Educational Laboratory.\n\n{{North Omaha}}\n\n[[Category:Schools in North Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Middle schools in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Public middle schools in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Magnet schools in Nebraska]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8804:1e00:5750:1423:897d:32dc:a37b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McMillan_Magnet_Center"}
{"title_page": "Thuraimugam", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thuraimugam\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[K. Rajeshwar]]\n| producer       = Georgi George\n| writer         = K. Rajeshwar\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[C. Arunpandian]]|[[Shobana]]|[[Livingston (actor)|Livingston]]|[[Alex (actor)|Alex]]|[[Poornam Vishwanathan]]|[[Charle]]|[[Jai Ganesh]]|[[Kavitha (actress)|Kavitha]]}}\n| music          = [[Adithyan]]\n| cinematography = G. P. Krishna\n| editing        = [[B. Lenin]]<br>[[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| distributor    =\n| studio         = Megnam Productions\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1996|10|25}}\n| runtime        = 150 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Thuraimugam''''' (English : Port) is a [[Tamil films of 1996|1996]] [[Tamil language|Tamil]]  [[crime film|crime]] [[drama film]] directed by [[K. Rajeshwar]]. The film features [[C. Arunpandian]] and [[Shobana]] in the lead roles, with [[Livingston (actor)|Livingston]], [[Alex (actor)|Alex]], [[Poornam Vishwanathan]], [[Charle]], [[Jai Ganesh]] and [[Kavitha (actress)|Kavitha]] playing supporting roles. The film, produced by Georgi George, had musical score by [[Adithyan]] and was released on 25 October 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/thuraimugam-movie/12014|title=Thuraimugam (1996)|accessdate=2016-11-07|publisher=gomolo.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/cgi-bin/filmography/allCast.cgi?id=1982|title=Filmography of thuraimugam|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051203195051/http://www.cinesouth.com/cgi-bin/filmography/allCast.cgi?id=1982|archive-date=2005-12-03|accessdate=2016-11-07|publisher=cinesouth.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com/movies/Kollywood/Thurai_Mugam/8359|title=Find Tamil Movie Thurai Mugam|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202054757/http://www.jointscene.com/movies/Kollywood/Thurai_Mugam/8359|archive-date=2011-12-02|accessdate=2016-11-07|publisher=jointscene.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!msg/soc.culture.tamil/z1WmCTek-bw/NFEwRqSpWjwJ|title=Tamil Movie News--Deepavali \"Kutti News\" Edition |date=1996-09-11|accessdate=2016-11-07|publisher=groups.google.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nNaamam ([[Jai Ganesh]]) was a union leader respected by the labourers, he lived with his wife Punniyalakshmi ([[Kavitha (actress)|Kavitha]]) and two children in abject poverty. He even went on [[hunger strike]] over a salary dispute. The last day of the hunger strike, he was poisoned by his friend Ethiraj ([[Alex (actor)|Alex]]) and thus Ethiraj became the new union leader. Punniyalakshmi and her children suffered hunger, thus her baby girl died. Punniyalakshmi, with her child Johnny into her arms, jumped into the sea. They were later saved by labourers and admitted at the hospital. There, Johnny ran away from his mother.\n\nMany years later, Johnny ([[C. Arunpandian]]) became a gangster in a port city. Johnny had met his mother but he still hated her and he preferred to maintain the distance between them. The police Inspector Alexander Veeramuthu (Georgi George) waited for the right moment to arrest Johnny. Johnny was the friend of the transsexual Gowri Kumar ([[Livingston (actor)|Livingston]]) who was Ethiraj's son. One night, Gowri Kumar killed a prostitute. Johnny was then wrongly accused with Gowri Kumar for killing the prostitute. At the court, Gowri Kumar was sentenced to life imprisonment, whereas Johnny got a seven-year prison sentence.\n\nSeven years later, Johnny is urged to take revenge on the public prosecutor Ramanujam ([[Poornam Vishwanathan]]). His first attempt to murder him fails. So he decides to spoil his daughter Rukkumani's ([[Shobana]]) life and he even stops her wedding. In the meantime, Johnny clashes with the smuggler Ethiraj. When Ethiraj's henchmen try to kill Johnny, his mother Punniyalakshmi intervenes and dies. Ethiraj then dies in a car accident. Fate leads Johnny to marry Rukkumani. Rukkumani then changes him into a good person and Johnny starts to work as a labourer in the port. All goes well until Gowri Kumar is released from jail. What transpires next forms the rest of the story.\n\n==Cast==\n\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[C. Arunpandian]] as Johnny\n*[[Shobana]] as Rukkumani\n*[[Livingston (actor)|Livingston]] as Gowri Kumar\n*[[Alex (actor)|Alex]] as Ethiraj\n*[[Poornam Vishwanathan]] as Ramanujam\n*[[Charle]] as Jana\n*[[Jai Ganesh]] as Naamam (guest appearance)\n*[[Kavitha (actress)|Kavitha]] as Punniyalakshmi\n*Georgi George as Inspector Alexander Veeramuthu\n*[[K. R. Savithri]] as Mangalam, Rukkumani's mother\n*[[Disco Shanti]]\n*[[Anusha (actress)|Anusha]] as Radha, Rukkumani's father\n*[[Shakeela]]\n*[[M. R. Krishnamurthy]] as Narayanan\n*Manager Cheena as Doctor\n*Master Udaya Raj as Johnny (child)\n*[[Mahendran (actor)|Mahendran]] as Alexander Veeramuthu\n*Nellai Kabilan\n*Jayamani\n*Vincent Roy\n{{colend}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Thuraimugam\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Adithyan]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1994\n| recorded   = 1994\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 28:38\n| label      =\n| producer   = [[Adithyan]]\n| prev_title = [[Kizhakku Mugam]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Roja Malare]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n}}\n\nThe film score and the soundtrack were composed by [[film composer]] [[Adithyan]]. The soundtrack, released in 1994, features 6 tracks with lyrics written by the film director [[K. Rajeshwar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://play.raaga.com/tamil/album/Thuraimugam-songs-T0004072|title=Thuraimugam Songs|accessdate=2016-11-07|publisher=play.raaga.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saavn.com/s/album/tamil/Thuraimugam-2010/ZNsHc63j9J0_|title=Thuraimugam Songs|accessdate=2016-11-07|publisher=saavn.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/soc.culture.tamil/VMl6yIi8sXs/NMkEiChKcsgJ|title=Ilaiyaraaja's recent compositions (was Re: May Madham)|date=1994-09-11|accessdate=2016-11-07|publisher=groups.google.com}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Track !! Song !! Singer(s) !! Duration\n|-\n|1 || 'Chinna Chinna' || [[K. S. Chithra]] || 5:32\n|-\n|2 || 'Rukkumani Wrongapora' || K. S. Chithra || 4:37\n|-\n|3 || 'Soda Bottle ' || [[Suresh Peters]], [[Adithyan]] || 5:46\n|-\n|4 || 'Yeanda Porandha' || M. G. Sundar || 4:21\n|-\n|5 || 'Amma Amma' || Suryaraja || 4:11\n|-\n|6 || 'Raja Rajavin' || [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]], K. S. Chithra || 4:11\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1996 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s action drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Thuraimugam\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[K. Rajeshwar]]\n| producer       = Georgi George\n| writer         = K. Rajeshwar\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[C. Arunpandian]]|[[Shobana]]|[[Livingston (actor)|Livingston]]|[[Alex (actor)|Alex]]|[[Poornam Vishwanathan]]|[[Charle]]|[[Jai Ganesh]]|[[Kavitha (actress)|Kavitha]]}}\n| music          = [[Adithyan]]\n| cinematography = G. P. Krishna\n| editing        = [[B. Lenin]]<br>[[V. T. Vijayan]]\n| distributor    =\n| studio         = Megnam Productions\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|1996|10|25}}\n| runtime        = 150 minutes\n| co