[Edmonds, Washington]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Korean hip hop|Hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter|record producer|actor|model|dancer|choreographer|entrepreneur}}\n| years_active     = 2008\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[JYP Entertainment|JYP]]|[[SidusHQ]]|[[AOMG]]|H1GHR Music|[[Roc Nation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rocnation.com/jay-park-signs-roc-nation/|title=Jay Park Signs with Roc Nation - ROCNATION|date=July 21, 2017|publisher=|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822175710/http://rocnation.com/jay-park-signs-roc-nation/|archive-date=August 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rocnation.com/artists/|title=ROC NATION Artists|publisher=}}</ref>}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Art of Movement]]|[[2PM]]|[[JYP Nation]]|[[Cha Cha Malone]]|[[Dok2]]|[[The Quiett]]|[[Dumbfoundead]]|[[SoReal Cru]]|[[Gray]]|[[Loco (rapper)|Loco]]|[[Simon Dominic]]|[[Hoody (singer)|Hoody]]|[[Higher Brothers]]|}}\n| website          = {{URL|jaypark.com/}}\n| module           = {{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul = {{linktext|\ubc15|\uc7ac|\ubc94}}\n|hanja  = {{linktext|\u6734|\u8f09|\u7bc4}}\n|rr= Bak Jae-beom\n|mr= Pak Chaeb\u014fm\n|child=yes}}\n| module2 = {{Infobox person\n|child=yes\n|signature=File: jayparksignature.svg\n}}}}\n\n'''Jay Park''' ([[Korean name]]: '''Park Jae-beom''' ([[Hangul]]: \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94; [[Hanja]]: \u6734\u8f09\u7bc4); born April 25, 1987) is a Korean American rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer, dancer, choreographer, entrepreneur, actor,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jay Park Signs With Roc Nation: 'This Is a Win for Asian Americans'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7873936/jay-park-roc-nation-signed|work=Billboard}}</ref> member of the [[Seattle]]-based [[breakdancing|b-boy]] crew [[Art of Movement]] (AOM), and founder and CEO of the independent hip hop record labels [[AOMG]] and H1GHR Music.<ref name=jayparkofficialbio>{{cite web|title=Jay Park Bio |url=http://www.jaypark.com/eng/bio/bio.php |publisher=jaypark.com |accessdate=December 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123154253/http://jaypark.com/eng/bio/bio.php |archivedate=January 23, 2013 }}</ref>\nPark started as a [[b-boy]] and dancer, known for his charismatic performances and stage presence.<ref name=mtv-world-stage-bieber-upstaged /><ref name=mtvasia-world-stage-bio>{{cite web|title=MTV World Stage Live In Malaysia Makes Spectacular Return To Sunway Lagoon On 14 July! |url=http://worldstage.mtvasia.com/news.php?id=1 |publisher=MTV Asia |accessdate=December 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827194351/http://worldstage.mtvasia.com/news.php?id=1 |archivedate=August 27, 2012 }}</ref> Park was described as a \"born entertainer\" by Korean pop singer [[Patti Kim (singer)|Patti Kim]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|title=Jay Park Covers Legend Patti Kim's \"Love Is a Two Letter Word\"|url=http://www.soompi.com/2012/04/01/park-jaebum-covers-legend-patti-kims-love-is-a-two-letter-word/|publisher=Soompi|date = April 1, 2012| accessdate=December 29, 2012}}</ref> and ''[[The New York Times]]'' quoted the president of digital music distributor DFSB Kollective describing Park as \"not just an artist, but also his own PR agent, fan club president, and TV network.\"<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|title=Bringing K-Pop to the West|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/business/global/using-social-media-to-bring-korean-pop-music-to-the-west.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=December 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPark initially rose to fame as the leader of South Korean [[boy band]] [[2PM]], formed by record label [[JYP Entertainment]] in 2008, after having previously been a trainee for four years.<ref name=\"hotblood\">{{cite web| title =\uc5f4\ud608\ub0a8\uc544 JYP 13\uc870, \uc313\uc544\uc628 \uc2e4\ub825 \uccab \uacf5\uac1c![\ud3ec\ud1a0\uc5d4] |trans-title=The 13 member JYP group \"Hot Blood\" reveals their talent | author = Yu, Yong-seok | publisher =Newsen | date = March 8, 2008 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200803082201291002&search=title&searchstring=jyp | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=Korean}}</ref> In September 2009, Park returned home to Seattle after comments he wrote about Korea in 2005 as a teenager were publicized by the Korean media; Park officially left the group in early 2010.<ref name=\"departure\">{{cite web|title=\uc7ac\ubc94 2PM \uc790\uc9c4\ud0c8\ud1f4, \ub9c8\ub140\uc0ac\ub0e5 \ub17c\ub780 \ubd84\ubd84 \ud6c4\ud3ed\ud48d \uc608\uace0 |trans-title=Park Jaebeom voluntarily withdraws from 2PM, consequence of witch hunting |author=Park, Se-yeon |publisher=Newsen via JoinsMSN |date=September 9, 2009 |url=http://news.joins.com/article/3765522?ctg=1503|accessdate=February 1, 2017|language=ko}}</ref> In March 2010, Park uploaded a cover video of [[B.o.B]]'s hit \"[[Nothin' on You]]\", with his own rap and lyrics, to YouTube,<ref name=\"nothingonyou\">{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 \"\ub098 \ub54c\ubb38\uc5d0 2PM \uba64\ubc84\ub4e4 \ubbf8\uc6cc\ud558\uc9c0 \ub9d0\uae38\" (Park Jaebeom: \"Do not hate the 2PM members because of me\") | author =Hankyung.com | publisher =bntnews| date = March 16, 2010 |url =http://bntnews.hankyung.com/apps/news?popup=0&nid=04&c1=04&c2=04&c3=00&nkey=201003161733353&mode=sub_view | accessdate = June 6, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> which went [[viral video|viral]] and reached over 2,000,000 views in less than 24 hours,<ref name=\"video\">{{cite web|title=Korean Sound Wave: Korean-American Star's Popularity Extends To New York |author=Dodley, Lewis |publisher=NY1.com |date=May 5, 2012 |url=http://www.ny1.com/content/special_reports/asianamerican_heritage_week_2012/162017/korean-sound-wave--korean-american-star-s-popularity-extends-to-new-york |accessdate=June 27, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601050754/http://www.ny1.com/content/special_reports/asianamerican_heritage_week_2012/162017/korean-sound-wave--korean-american-star-s-popularity-extends-to-new-york |archivedate=June 1, 2012 }}</ref> leading to the release of Park's first EP, ''[[Count on Me (EP)|Count on Me]]'' in July 2010, which debuted at number one on the ''[[Gaon Chart|Gaon]]'' chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon |title=Gaon Weekly album chart |date=July 13, 2010 |publisher=Gaon |accessdate=July 13, 2010 |language=ko |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CRtw7nH4?url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon |archive-date=November 25, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Park returned to South Korea in June 2010 for the filming of ''Hype Nation'',<ref name=\"hypenation\">{{cite web |url=http://news.nate.com/view/20100618n18069 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, 1\ucc9c\ud32c \ud658\ud638\uc18d 9\uac1c\uc6d4\ub9cc\uc5d0 \u97d3 \uc804\uaca9\ubc29\ubb38 (Jaebeom visits Korea in 9 months with cheers of thousands of fans) |date=June 18, 2010 |publisher=Nate |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> while being represented by Digital Media Wire's CEO and entertainment attorney Ned Sherman,<ref name=\"nedsherman\">{{cite web| title =Entertainment Attorney Ned Sherman Representing Jay Park on Global Entertainment Career | publisher =PR Newswire| date = May 28, 2010 |url =http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/entertainment-attorney-ned-sherman-representing-jay-park-on-global-entertainment-career-95102834.html | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> and in July 2010, Park signed a contract with [[SidusHQ]], one of the largest agencies in South Korea, re-debuting as a solo singer and an actor.<ref name=\"sidus\">{{cite web |url=http://news.donga.com/3/all/20100716/29929139/3 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc2f8\uc774\ub354\uc2a4HQ\uc640 \uacc4\uc57d\u2026\ubcf8\uaca9 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ud65c\ub3d9 (Jaebeom contracts with SidusHQ, officially starts national activities) |date=July 16, 2010 |publisher=Donga News |accessdate=June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nPark's first mini album, ''[[Take a Deeper Look]]'', released in 2011, went [[List of music recording certifications|multi-platinum]] in South Korea. Park became the first ever artist crowned winner on a debut stage by winning on [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]]' ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' with \"[[Abandoned (song)|Abandoned]]\",<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|title=Jay Park Makes Epic Comeback with K-Chart Win, Billboard ranking |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/node/317187/jay-park-make |newspaper=Manila Bulletin |author=Hicap, Jonathan M. |date=May 7, 2011 |accessdate=June 25, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728232211/http://www.mb.com.ph/node/317187/jay-park-make |archivedate=July 28, 2013 }}</ref> and was the only solo artist to win \"Record of the Year\" at the [[Golden Disk Awards#Bonsang|2011 Golden Disk Awards]].<ref name=\"bonsang\">{{cite web | title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \uace8\ub4e0\ub514\uc2a4\ud06c \ubcf8\uc0c1 \uc218\uc0c1\uc5d0 \"\uacf0\ubc29\uc640~\" \uc778\uc0ac (Jay Park greets fans with \"Konbanwa\" as he receives Golden Disk Bonsang Award) | publisher =ISPlus | date =January 11, 2012 | url =http://isplus.live.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?Total_Id=7115323 | archive-url =https://archive.today/20121209034216/http://isplus.live.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?Total_Id=7115323 | url-status =dead | archive-date =December 9, 2012 | accessdate =June 22, 2012 | language =ko }}</ref> Later in 2011, Park released singles \"[[Demon (song)|Demon]]\", \"[[Girlfriend (Jay Park song)|Girlfriend]]\", and \"Star\", co-starred in the Korean movie, ''[[Mr. Idol]]'', and joined the cast of KBS' ''[[Immortal Songs: Singing the Legend|Immortal Songs 2]]''.<ref name=mridol /> At the end of 2011, Park released an EP, ''[[New Breed (Jay Park album)|New Breed Part 1]]''; the precursor to Park's first full-length album.\n\nIn February 2012, Jay Park released his first full-length album, ''[[New Breed (Jay Park album)|New Breed]]'', quickly topping charts in South Korea and internationally, and went multi-platinum in less than a week.<ref name=\"hanteo\">{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 1\uc704, 10\uc77c \ub9cc\uc5d0 8\ub9cc\uc7a5 \ud310\ub9e4 '\ud55c\ud130 \uc8fc\uac04\ucc28\ud2b8 \uc62c\ud0ac' (Park Jaebeom is No.1, sells 80,000 copies in 10 days, achieves an \"all-kill\" on the Hanteo Weekly Chart) | date = February 29, 2012 | publisher =TV Report via Nate|url =http://news.nate.com/view/20120229n04671 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Park also released an English [[mixtape]], ''[[Fresh Air: Breathe It]]'', which became the first mixtape by an Asian artist to achieve gold status on [[DatPiff]] for surpassing 100,000 downloads.<ref name=100k-gold-datpiff-mixtape>{{cite web|title=Jay Park becomes the first Asian singer to receive the Gold Title |url=http://en.korea.com/blog/enter/k-pop/jay-park-becomes-the-first-asian-singer-to-receive-the-gold-title/ |publisher=Korea.com |accessdate=December 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129035337/http://en.korea.com/blog/enter/k-pop/jay-park-becomes-the-first-asian-singer-to-receive-the-gold-title/ |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref> Following the release of ''New Breed'' in 2012, Park successfully held his first solo concert in [[Seoul]], as well as embarking on tours around Asia and Australia. Park headlined the Verizon APAHM Tour in the United States, and was the closing act at [[MTV World Stage Live in Malaysia|MTV World Stage Live in Malaysia 2012]]. Also in 2012, Park returned to KBS' ''Immortal Songs 2'', became a fixed panel member on MBC's ''Come to Play'', and hosted [[TVN (Southeast Asia)|tvN]]'s ''[[Saturday Night Live Korea]]''.<ref name=snl-mnet /> Park became a permanent cast member of ''Saturday Night Live Korea'' in early 2013.<ref name=snl-first-ep-choi-min-soo /> In 2014, Jay Park performed 2014 South by Southwest ([[SXSW]]) as a Korean representative pop singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2014/03/indie-band-crying-nut-release-march-tour-dates-in-us|title=Indie band Crying Nut release March tour dates in U.S. - allkpop.com|publisher=}}</ref> Jay Park released his album ''Worldwide'' in November 2015.<ref name=\"Worldwide\">{{cite web|title=Worldwide|url=http://www.soompi.com/2015/10/29/jay-parks-new-album-features-27-of-the-hottest-rappers-in-the-hip-hop-scene/|website=Soompi|accessdate=November 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Jay Park announced a partnership with [[Jay-Z]]'s entertainment agency [[Roc Nation]], garnering worldwide recognition surrounding his foray into the US market as the first Asian American signed to the label.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/08/asia/jay-park-jay-z-roc-nation/index.html|title=Jay Park: from K-pop to Jay-Z|work=CNN|last=Liu|first=Marian|date=2017-10-09|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2018, Park dropped his debut US music capsule, ''Ask Bout Me''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/07/jay-park-ask-bout-me-capsule-feat-2-chainz-vic-mensa-rich-the-kid-gashi|title=Stream Jay Park's 'Ask Bout Me' f/ 2 Chainz, Vic Mensa, Rich the Kid, and Gashi|work=Complex|last=Diep|first=Eric|date=2018-07-19|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early years===\nBorn in [[Edmonds, Washington|Edmonds]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], in the [[Seattle metropolitan area]], Park showed great interest in hip hop music and breakdancing at a young age. Park attended [[Edmonds Woodway High School|Edmonds Woodway]]  and [[Meadowdale High School (Washington)|Meadowdale High School]], where he spent most of his break and lunch times practicing dance with friends.<ref name=koreanupdates-interview>{{cite web|title=[@JAYBUMAOM] Get to know further about Jay Park in 5 minutes|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20110510n08470|publisher=Nate|accessdate=February 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title =A Seattleite in Korea | author = Matson, Andrew | newspaper =The Seattle Times | date = April 27, 2012 |url =http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/matsononmusic/2018081834_a_seattleite_in_korea.html | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> Park started listening to [[hip hop]] and [[rap]] music in his early teens, and spent time learning and writing raps himself during [[high school]].<ref name=imagine-tv-interview>{{cite web|title=Jay Park speaks to Imagine TV Network|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a72j4Jf9btk|publisher=Imagine TV Network|accessdate=February 23, 2013}}</ref>  In 2003, Park became one of the first members of the Seattle-based [[b-boy]] crew [[Art of Movement]] (AOM). In 2004, Park's mother, seeing how her son spent more time breakdancing than studying, suggested he audition for Korea-based [[JYP Entertainment]], which brought him to Korea in January 2005 to receive further training in dancing, rapping, singing, and the Korean language.<ref>{{cite web|title =Complex Exclusive: Jay Park Talks U.S. Album, Covering B.o.B, and Life After 2PM | author = Kwak, Donnie | publisher =Complex Music | date = February 22, 2011 |url =http://www.complex.com/music/2011/02/complex-exclusive-jay-park-talks-us-album-covering-bob-and-life-after-2pm | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> Park eventually completed his university education at [[Dankook University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jaypark.net/profile-2/ |title=Profile |publisher=Jay Park Network |accessdate=January 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112134537/http://jaypark.net/profile-2/ |archivedate=January 12, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132009: 2PM===\n[[File:2 PM Korean band.jpg|left|thumb|2PM during a press conference for ''[[Wonder Girls]] The First Wonder Live In Bangkok'' in February 2009]]\nPark first appeared through [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s ''Hot Blood Men'', a documentary-style reality program that showed the future members of One Day, split as idol groups [[2AM (band)|2AM]] and [[2PM]], in training.  Park, finishing at the top spot with the most fan votes, became the leader of 2PM.<ref name=\"hotblood\" /> On September 4, 2008, 2PM debuted with the song \"[[10 Out of 10]]\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|10\uc810 \ub9cc\uc810\uc5d0 10\uc810}}; Revised Romanization: ''Ship Jeom Manjeome Ship Jeom'') on the music program ''[[M! Countdown]]'' after the release of their first mini-album, ''[[Hottest Time of the Day]]'', a few days prior.<ref>{{cite web | title ='\ubc15\uc9c4\uc601\uc758 \uc790\uc874\uc2ec'\ubcf4\uc774\ubc34\ub4dc 2PM,4\uc77c \ub370\ubdd4 (JYP's pride: boyband 2PM debuts on the 4th) | author =Yi, Wu-in | publisher =CNBNEWS | date =September 4, 2008 | url =http://news.cnbnews.com/category/read.html?bcode=49980 | accessdate =June 22, 2012 | language =ko | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20130121070804/http://news.cnbnews.com/category/read.html?bcode=49980 | archivedate =January 21, 2013 }}</ref>\nAside from 2PM's music activities, Park created the song \"Jeong\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|\uc815}}) with [[Yeeun]] of the [[Wonder Girls]] for the original soundtrack of the television drama ''[[Conspiracy in the Court]]'', and featured on V.O.S's \"To Luv...\".<ref name=\"jeong\">{{cite web| title =V.O.S \ucd5c\ud604\uc900 '\uc704\ub4dc \uc720' \uc790\ud544 \uc545\ubcf4 \uc790\uc120 \uacbd\ub9e4 (V.O.S Choi Hyunjoon 'With You' puts out handwritten musical notes for charity) | author = TV Daily | publisher =Nate | date = June 9, 2009 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20090609n17801 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> He also participated in special stage performances, such as Navi's \"Heart Damage\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|\ub9c8\uc74c\uc774 \ub2e4\uccd0\uc11c}}; Revised Romanization: ''Maeumi Dachyeoseo'') on May 3, 2009,<ref>{{cite web| title =2PM \uc7ac\ubc94, \ub098\ube44 '\ub9c8\uc74c\uc774 \ub2e4\uccd0\uc11c' \ud1b5\ud574 \uc5d0\uc774\ud2b8\uc5d0 \uc624\ub9c8\uc8fc \uc804\ud574 (2PM Jaebeom, doing \"homage\" of Navi's \"Damaged Heart\") | author = Park, Se-yeon | publisher =Newsen | date = May 5, 2009 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200905040803161001&search=title&searchstring=%C0%E7%B9%FC | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> and [[K.Will]]'s \"One Drop per Second\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|1\ucd08\uc5d0 \ud55c\ubc29\uc6b8}}; Revised Romanization: ''Il Choe Hanbangul'') on June 20, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| title =2PM \uc7ac\ubc94, \ucf00\uc774\uc70c \ud6c4\uc18d \ud65c\ub3d9 \uc9c0\uc6d0 \uc0ac\uaca9 '\ud30d\ud30d' (2PM Jaebeom, helps K.Will's activities) | author = Kim, Hyeong-woo | publisher =Newsen | date = June 19, 2009 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200906191949181002&search=title&searchstring=%C0%E7%B9%FC | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> In addition to ''[[Idol Show]]'' and ''Wild Bunny'' with fellow 2PM members, he also became a regular cast member in several variety programs, including ''[[Star King (TV series)|Star King]]'' and ''Introducing a Star's Friend''.<ref>{{cite web| title ='\uc2a4\uce5c\uc18c' \ucef4\ubc31 \uc7ac\ubc94, \ud55c\uc720\uc774 \ub193\uace0 \ucc2c\uc131\uacfc \uc0bc\uac01\uad00\uacc4 \ubcf8\uaca9\ud654 (Jaebeom comes back to \"Introducing a Star's Friend,\" fights over Han Uee with Chansung in a love triangle showdown) | author= Lee, Mi-hye | publisher =Newsen | date = July 13, 2009 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?news_uid=345069 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> In August 2009, he and [[Kara (South Korean band)|Kara]] band member, [[Nicole Jung]], became the new hosts for a cultural variety show called ''Nodaji''.<ref>{{cite web| title =\uc720\uc801 \ucc3e\uc544 \ubcf4\ubb3c\uc9c0\ub3c4 \ub9cc\ub4e4\uae30 (Making treasure map by searching through the historic sites) | author = The Hankyoreh | publisher =Nate | date = August 8, 2009 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20090828n14856 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn September 4, 2009, unfavorable comments towards Korea were found on Park's personal Myspace account from 2005. The comments, written in English to a friend, were translated by Korean media, quickly spreading across hundreds of news articles. Park expressed deep remorse and shame over his forgotten words and issued an official apology, explained the unhappiness that he experienced during his early days as a trainee in an unfamiliar country where he lacked family, the ability to easily communicate, and an understanding of the culture.<ref>{{cite web | title =JYP, 2PM \uc7ac\ubc94 \ud55c\uad6d\ube44\ud558 \uacf5\uc2dd \uc0ac\uacfc\ubb38 \"\uba38\ub9ac\uc219\uc5ec \uc0ac\uacfc\ub4dc\ub9bd\ub2c8\ub2e4\" (JYP releases official apology for Jaebeom of 2PM's insults about Korea, \"I bow my head and apologise\") | author =Lee, Mi-hye | publisher =Newsen via JoinsMSN | date =September 5, 2009 | url =http://article.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=3761263&ctg=15 | accessdate =April 30, 2012 | language =ko | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20120724110937/http://article.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=3761263&ctg=15 | archivedate =July 24, 2012 }}</ref> Although outraged protesters demanded that Park should be removed from 2PM, JYP Entertainment's CEO, Park Jin-young, stated on September 7, 2009, that he was going to continue as a part of the group.<ref>{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc9c4\uc601 \"\uc7ac\ubc94, 2PM \ud0c8\ud1f4\ub294 \uc5c6\ub2e4\" \uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5 (JYP releases official notice \"Jaebeom's withdrawal of 2PM will never happen\") | author = Lee, Eon-hyoek | publisher =Nate | date = September 7, 2009 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20090828n14856 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> The following day, Park announced on his official fancafe that he would be leaving the group to calm the situation and return to his hometown, Seattle, Washington. He also apologized to the other 2PM members, and promised that he would \"come back a better person\".<ref name=\"departure\" /> Park Jin-young then confirmed that 2PM would continue as a six-member group.<ref>{{cite news| title =Will Fallen Idol Star Make Comeback? | author = Han, Sang-hee | newspaper =The Korea Times | date = September 18, 2009 |url =http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/09/201_52095.html | accessdate = April 30, 2012}}</ref> Additionally, due to the sensitive topic of Park's departure, all 2PM members were withdrawn from their regular appearances on variety shows,<ref>{{cite web| title =2PM \uc608\ub2a5 \ucd9c\uc5f0 \uc790\uc81c \uc65c? \"\ud32c\ub4e4\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \uc608\uc758 \ucc28\uc6d0\" (Why is 2PM abstaining from appearing in variety shows? \"To be courteous to the fans\") | author = Newsen | publisher =Newsen | date = November 15, 2009 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200911151001021002# | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> and the final episode of their reality show, ''Wild Bunny'', was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web| title ='\uc7ac\ubc94 \ud6c4\ud3ed\ud48d' 2PM '\uc640\uc77c\ub4dc \ubc14\ub2c8' \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9\ud68c \ubb34\uae30\ud55c \uc5f0\uae30 (2PM Wild Bunny finale postponed indefinitely) | author = Cha, Yeon | publisher =Newsen | date = September 9, 2009 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200909080950181001 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Park's vocals would not be removed from the older songs he promoted with 2PM, but he would be absent from the newer tracks, and the remaining six members of 2PM re-filmed their music video for \"[[Heartbeat (2PM song)|Heartbeat]]\" without Park on October 31, 2009.<ref>{{cite web| title =2PM '\uc7ac\ubc94 \uc5c6\uc774' 2\uc77c \ucef4\ubc31, \uc7ac\ubc94 \ub179\uc74c \uace1 \uc218\ub85d \uad00\uc2ec (2PM will come back on the 2nd without Jaebeom, Interest over whether Jaebeom's recordings will be included or not) | author = Newsen | publisher =Newsen | date = November 2, 2009 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200911020721291002 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n2PM's first official album was titled ''[[1:59PM]]'', to symbolize Park's absence, according to the six remaining members.<ref>{{cite web| title =2PM \"1:59PM\uc740 \uc7ac\ubc94\uc744 \uae30\ub2e4\ub9b0\ub2e4\ub294 \uc758\ubbf8\" (2PM's 1:59PM means that we will wait for Jaebeom) | author = Yonhap | publisher =Nate | date = November 26, 2009 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20091126n06315 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Through their acceptance speeches at end-of-year award shows for \"[[Again & Again (2PM song)|Again & Again]]\", the members thanked Park and reiterated their wish for his return. At the [[Mnet Asian Music Awards]], the group paid homage to him during their performance of \"Again & Again\" with a spotlight shown over his usual position in the dance formation and his lines left unsung.<ref>{{cite web| title =2PM, MAMA \uc7ac\ubc94 \uc704\ud55c \ud2b9\ubcc4 \ud37c\ud3ec\uba3c\uc2a4 \ub72c\ub2e4 (2PM will have a performance dedicated to Jaebeom) | author = Kim, Hyeong-u | publisher =Newsen | date = November 21, 2009 |url =http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200911211356031002 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J2_hMiMqyZk |title= MAMA - 2PM thank you Speech! |date= January 5, 2010 |publisher=Youtube |accessdate= April 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2010: YouTube career and solo debut===\nSoon after Park returned to the United States, the South Korean public changed their perspective on the matter when they realized that his Myspace messages had been severely mistranslated and taken out of context, in addition to strong fan support for Park's return.<ref name=\"tinzarsherman\">{{cite web|title=Facebook, YouTube, Twitter, MySpace and the Story of Jay Park (AKA Jaebeom Park) |author=Sherman, Tinzar |publisher=Digital Media Wire |date=March 18, 2010 |url=http://digitalmediawire.com/2010/03/18/facebook-youtube-twitter-myspace-and-the-story-of-jay-park-aka-jaebeom-park |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Park was seen at [[b-boy]] battles with fellow [[Art of Movement]] members during his time in Seattle. However, on February 25, with Park's comeback looking more and more likely, JYP suddenly announced that Jay Park's contract with them had been terminated, citing a separate \"personal mistake\" that Park had made in 2009.<ref>{{cite web| title =\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc601\uad6c\ud0c8\ud1f4..JYP \"\uac1c\uc778\uc0ac\uc815\uc73c\ub85c \uc804\uc18d \uacc4\uc57d \ud574\uc9c0\" (Jaebeom's permanent leave...JYP \"Broke off exclusive contract due to personal reasons\") | author = Lee, Soo-hyun | publisher =Nate | date = February 25, 2010 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20100225n22746 | accessdate = June 6, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> JYP would make reference to this unknown event several times in 2010, but would never elaborate on any details. This termination had been agreed by all six members of 2PM and led to fan boycotts on 2PM-endorsed products. Protests for Park's return to the group began to take place, not only in South Korea, but internationally as well.<ref>{{cite web| title =\uc7ac\ubc94\uc5d0\uc11c \ud604\uc911\uae4c\uc9c0\u2026\u65b0 \ubb38\ud654\uad8c\ub825 '\ud32c\ud074\ub7fd' (From Jay Park to Hyunjoong...NEW culture authority \"Fan Club\") | author =Osen | publisher =Osen| date = March 21, 2010 |url =http://osen.mt.co.kr/news/view.html?gid=G1003190165 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Various Jay Park-dedicated forums and fansites all over the world organized silent protests and flash dance mobs.<ref name=\"tinzarsherman\" /> Fans also hired a plane with a banner showing \"J, what time is it now?\" to fly over Seattle, and was broadcast on Seattle-based radio stations.<ref>{{cite web | title =Fans Beg Former Korean Boy Band Member To Return | author =Mayfield, Travis | publisher =Edmonds KOMO | date =September 28, 2009 | url =http://edmonds.komonews.com/content/fans-beg-former-korean-boy-band-member-return | accessdate =August 29, 2012 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20130127045641/http://edmonds.komonews.com/content/fans-beg-former-korean-boy-band-member-return | archivedate =January 27, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jaebeom's fans take it to the sky! |publisher=allkpop |date=September 27, 2009 |url=http://www.allkpop.com/2009/09/jaebeoms_fans_take_it_to_the_sky |accessdate=August 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025231413/http://www.allkpop.com/2009/09/jaebeoms_fans_take_it_to_the_sky |archivedate=October 25, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn several occasions, Park was the number one trending topic on [[Twitter]], even topping the [[Oscars]] on March 8.<ref>{{cite news| title =Current Twitter trends: Jay Park, Oscars... | newspaper =The Independent | date = March 8, 2010 |url =https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/current-twitter-trends-jay-park-oscars-1918162.html | accessdate = April 30, 2012}}</ref> Park's fans revealed plans to release a self-produced album in his honor on March 27 to commemorate the 200th day anniversary of his departure from Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title='\uc7ac\ubc94 \uc704\ud55c' \ud32c\ub4e4 \uc790\uc791\uc568\ubc94 27\uc77c \uc74c\uc6d0\uacf5\uac1c (Fans' self recorded album dedicated to Jaebeom will release on the 27th) |publisher=Seoul Newspaper NTN |date=March 15, 2010 |url=http://ntn.seoul.co.kr/main.php?cmd=news/news_view&idx=26498 |accessdate=April 30, 2012 |language=ko |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320095422/http://ntn.seoul.co.kr/main.php?cmd=news%2Fnews_view&idx=26498 |archivedate=March 20, 2012 }}</ref> However, because the album had been in preparation since January and public opinion on 2PM had since changed, the fans decided it would be in the best interest to not release the CD, and instead, mailed 10\u201320 copies to Seattle, Park's hometown.<ref>{{cite web| title =\uc7ac\ubc94 \ud32c\ub4e4, \"\ud32c\uc568\ubc94 \ubc1c\ub9e4 \ubb34\uc0b0\" (Former 2PM idol group member's fans to release album) | author =Shim, Hwa-jun | publisher =Nate| date = March 26, 2010 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20100326n05534 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nPark created his own YouTube channel on March 15, \"jayparkaom\", with the first upload being his own version of \"[[Nothin' on You]]\", which went viral and reached over 2,000,000 views in less than 24 hours.<ref name=\"video\" /> In Korea, the original song by [[B.o.B]] and [[Bruno Mars]] topped the [[Cyworld]] music chart in a matter of hours upon the video's release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music.cyworld.com/note/post/post_view.asp?tid=22939515&pseq=378470 |title=Jay Park - Nothing On You |date=March 16, 2010 |publisher=Cyworld |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> \"Nothin' on You\" also reached number 1 on other music sites such as Dosirak, Melon, Mnet, Bugs, and Soribada, making $300,000 in sales through the effect of Park's video.<ref>{{cite web| title =\u7f8e \ud31d\uc2a4\ud0c0 B.O.B, \uc7ac\ubc94 \ub355 3\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uc774\uc0c1 \ub9e4\ucd9c '\ucf8c\uc7ac' (American Superstar B.o.B earns sales of over $300,000 because of Jaebeom) | publisher =Nate| date = March 17, 2010 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20100427n12398 | accessdate = April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> On June 15, 2010, B.o.B released \"Nothin' on You\" featuring Park, in South Korea, where he replaces Bruno Mars' vocals. His YouTube cover helped contribute to much of the song's success in Korea, with more than 5 million copies sold.<ref>{{cite web| title =\uc7ac\ubc94, B.O.B\uc640 \ub4c0\uc5e3 \uc2f1\uae00\ub85c \uad6d\ub0b4 \uccab \ud65c\ub3d9 (Jaebeom starts his first national activities with his duet single with B.O.B) | author =Yonhap | publisher =Naver| date = June 15, 2010 |url =http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=001&aid=0003331534 | accessdate = June 7, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Park subsequently thanked his fans for their support and continued to urge them not to hate remaining 2PM members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.nate.com/view/20100317n19115 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94 '\ud574\uc678\ud32c\uc9c8' \uc911\uc2ec\uc5d0 '\uc720\ud29c\ube0c' \uc788\ub2e4 (YouTube is the center of 'International Fangirling' of Jaebeom) |date=March 17, 2010 |publisher=Nate |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Art of Movement.jpg|right|thumb|Park and some members of his [[b-boy]] crew, [[Art of Movement]]]]\nHe appeared with fellow [[Art of Movement]] members at an annual Korean-American festival event called ''Project Korea III: KSA Cinderella Story'' at [[Rutgers University]], [[New Jersey]] on April 3, along with [[Ailee]] and [[Clara C]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ruksa.org/2010/03/29/project-korea-special-guest-revealed-along-with-after-party/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617190534/http://ruksa.org/2010/03/29/project-korea-special-guest-revealed-along-with-after-party/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 17, 2010 |title=Project Korea Special Performance Revealed along with After Party! |date=March 29, 2010 |publisher=Rutgers |accessdate=April 30, 2012 }}</ref> Videos of the event were uploaded onto internet portal sites, where footage of Park acting as an MC and dancing to [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s \"[[Single Ladies (Put a Ring on It)]]\" on stage drew much positive interest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.nate.com/view/20100404n05719 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, \u7f8e \ub300\ud559\ucd95\uc81c '\uc2f1\uae00\ub808\uc774\ub514' \uc139\uc2dc\ub304\uc2a4 \uc601\uc0c1 \uae5c\uc9dd\uacf5\uac1c (Jaebeom reveals sexy dance video of 'Single Ladies' from a college festival in US) |date=April 4, 2010 |publisher=Nate |accessdate=April 30, 2010|language=ko}}</ref> On April 24, [[Dumbfoundead]] released a free collaboration track featuring Park and [[Clara Chung]] on his website, titled \"Clouds\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music.dumbfoundead.com/track/clouds-ft-jay-park-clara |title=Clouds ft. Jay Park & Clara C |date=April 24, 2010 |publisher=Dumbfoundead.com |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nLos Angeles-based entertainment attorney Ned Sherman, CEO of Digital Media Wire, announced on May 28 that he was representing Park as his legal representative.<ref name=\"nedsherman\"/><ref>{{cite web| title =Buzz Watch- Jay Park (Park Jaebeom) Update | author = Sherman, Tinzar | publisher =Digital Media Wire| date = May 28, 2010 |url =http://www.dmwmedia.com/news/2010/05/28/buzz-watch-jay-park-park-jaebeom-update | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> Sherman and his wife Tinzar reached out to Park, after seeing Park's story and feeling bad about what happened to him during the MySpace controversy.<ref name=\"complex\">{{cite web|title=Complex Exclusive: Jay Park Talks U.S. Album, Covering B.o.B, and Life After 2PM |author=Kwak, Donnie |publisher=Complex Music |date=February 22, 2011 |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/02/complex-exclusive-jay-park-talks-us-album-covering-bob-and-life-after-2pm/page/2 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927042641/http://www.complex.com/music/2011/02/complex-exclusive-jay-park-talks-us-album-covering-bob-and-life-after-2pm/page/2 |archivedate=September 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Facebook, YouTube, Twitter, MySpace and the Story of Jay Park (AKA Jaebeom Park) |author=Sherman, Tinzar |publisher=Digital Media Wire |date=March 18, 2010 |url=http://www.dmwmedia.com/blog/%5Buser%5D/myspace-facebook-youtube-twitter-and-story-jay-park-aka-jaebeom-park |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403030637/http://www.dmwmedia.com/blog/%5Buser%5D/myspace-facebook-youtube-twitter-and-story-jay-park-aka-jaebeom-park |archivedate=April 3, 2012 }}</ref> The Shermans and Park worked on a lot of projects together, including his movie deal for ''Hype Nation'', an endorsement deal with dENiZEN, [[Levi Strauss & Co.]]'s new brand, and others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Talent Management |publisher=DMW Advisors |url=http://dmwadvisors.com/2011/07/global-talent-management/ |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901015225/http://dmwadvisors.com/2011/07/global-talent-management/ |archivedate=September 1, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =DMW Law Advisors | publisher =DMW Law Advisors| url =http://www.dmwlawadvisors.com/ | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPark returned to Korea on June 18 at [[Incheon International Airport]], to the biggest crowd ever seen at the airport, for the filming of ''Hype Nation''.<ref name=\"hypenation\" /> \"Park Jaebeom has returned\" became the biggest headline in Korea that day, and \"JayIsBack\" shot up immediately on the trending topics on Twitter on June 18 at 9:30 AM GMT.<ref>{{cite news| title =Current Twitter trends: Los Angeles Lakers win at the NBA Finals, death by firing squad, 'Jay is back' | newspaper =The Independent| date = June 18, 2010 |url =https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/current-twitter-trends-los-angeles-lakers-win-at-the-nba-finals-death-by-firing-squad-jay-is-back-2004310.html | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> Pictures of Park in ''Hype Nation'' were released on July 2,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=020&aid=0002148483 |author=Kim, Won-gyeom| title=\uc7ac\ubc94, '\ud558\uc774\ud504 \ub124\uc774\uc158' \ucd2c\uc601\uc0ac\uc9c4 \uacf5\uac1c (Jaebeom's 'Hype Nation' releases shooting pictures) |date=July 2, 2010 |publisher=Naver |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> and Park was able to meet with the Korean media for interviews for the first time, talking about his current activities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=001&aid=0003366305 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94 \"\ud55c\uad6d \uadf8\ub9ac\uc6e0\ub2e4..\ud55c\uae00\ub300\uc0ac \uc798 \uc678\uc6cc\uc838\" (Jaebeom \"missed Korea...can memorize Korean lines very well\") |date=July 6, 2010 |publisher=Naver |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> It was also revealed that his single \"[[Demon (song)|Demon]]\" would be included in ''Hype Nation'''s original soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=144&aid=0000121576 |title=We meet Jay! |date=July 6, 2010 |publisher=Naver |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported on July 8 that Park would sign a contract with [[SidusHQ]] for his domestic Korean activities in terms of acting and singing;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=108&aid=0002038312 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, \uad6d\ub0b4 \ucd5c\ub300\uae30\ud68d\uc0ac \uc2f8\uc774\ub354\uc2a4HQ\ub85c \uac04\ub2e4 (Jaebeom goes to one of the biggest national entertainment companies, SidusHQ) |date=July 8, 2010 |publisher=Naver via Star News |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> his management stated that he planned to redebut as a rookie artist,<ref name=\"sidus\" /> and the contract with SidusHQ was finalized on July 16.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://isplus.live.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=4317831&cloc= |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104015633/http://isplus.live.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=4317831&cloc= |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 4, 2013 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc2f8\uc774\ub354\uc2a4\ud589 \ud655\uc815...16\uc77c \uc624\ud6c4 \uacf5\uc2dd \ubc1c\ud45c (Jaebeom finalises with SidusHQ, official announcement on the afternoon of the 16th) |date=July 16, 2010 |author=Lee, Kyung-ran |newspaper=Ilgan Sports |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |language=ko }}</ref> Park released an EP titled ''[[Count on Me (EP)|Count on Me]]'' (Korean: {{lang|ko|\ubbff\uc5b4\uc904\ub798}}; Revised Romanization: ''Mideojullae'') containing three tracks, including a rearranged Korean version of \"Nothin' on You\", on July 13.<ref>{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 '\ubbff\uc5b4\uc904\ub798' \uacf5\uac1c \"\uc0c8\ubcbd\ub0ad\ubcf4\" \ub124\ud2f0\uc98c \ubc1c\uce75 (Jay Park releases 'Count on Me', netizens scream their happiness) | author = Kim, Su-jin | publisher =Nate| date = July 13, 2010 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20100713n02785 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> The English and Korean lyrics were written by Park himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=108&aid=0002038923 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc120\uc8fc\ubb38 4\ub9cc '\ubbff\uc5b4\uc904\ub798' \ub4e4\uc5b4\ubcf4\ub2c8..\uc2ec\uacbd\ud45c\ud604? (Jaebeom's 'Count on Me' pre-orders surpasse 40k copies) |date=July 12, 2010 |publisher=Star News |accessdate=June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> The song immediately reached number one on Cyworld and Bugs music charts, and also on other music sites such as Monkey3, Soribada, Dosirak, and Melon within the hour of its release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.etoday.co.kr/news/section/newsview.php?TM=news&SM=5102&idxno=335864 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, \uccab \uc194\ub85c '\ubbff\uc5b4\uc904\ub798' \ubc1c\ub9e4\ub418\uc790\ub9c8\uc790 1\uc704\u2026\uad00\uc2ec \ud3ed\ubc1c (Jaebeom's first solo single 'Count on Me' hits number 1 as soon as it's released, \"Interest overload\") |date=July 13, 2010 |publisher=Economy Today |accessdate=June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> The EP sold 21,989 physical copies on the first day of release, coming in at number one in sales and number seven in the overall ranking of albums released from January to July 13. Without any promotion on music shows, more than 41,316 copies sold, and the EP placed at number 32 on Gaon's year end chart,<ref name=\"gaonchart.co.kr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/notice/view.gaon?idx=36 |title=Gaon Weekly album chart |date=December 1, 2010 |publisher=Gaon |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> earning Park approximately 700 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=106&oid=108&aid=0002039190 |title=\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc74c\ubc18\ubc1c\ub9e4 \ud558\ub8e8\ub9cc\uc5d0 \uc5f0\uac04\ud310\ub9e4 \uc0ac\uc2e4\uc0c1 '\ud1b110' (Jaebeom's released album is in the Top 10 for annual sales within a day)|date=July 14, 2010 |publisher=Star News |accessdate=April 30, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nPark began working with singer, producer, and fellow [[Art of Movement|AOM]] member, [[Cha Cha Malone]], releasing \"[[Bestie (song)|Bestie]]\" in both Korean and English, and a duet titled \"[[Speechless (Jay Park & Cha Cha Malone song)|Speechless]]\".<ref name=cha-cha-soundcloud>{{cite web|title=Cha Cha Malone's stream on SoundCloud|url=http://soundcloud.com/chachamalone|publisher=Cha Cha Malone|accessdate=December 25, 2012}}</ref> Also in 2010, Park began collaborations and forming close ties with rappers [[Dok2]] and [[The Quiett]] of [[Illionaire Records]], titling the partnership \"AOM & 1llionaire\".\nOn September 5, Park participated in the 3rd [[Wong Fu Productions|International Secret Agents]] [[Los Angeles]] concert held in Cerritos, California, together with well-known YouTube celebrities such as [[Nigahiga|Ryan Higa]], [[KevJumba]], AJ Rafael, Alyssa Bernal, [[Far East Movement]], and [[America's Best Dance Crew]] Season 5 champions, [[Poreotix]]. Park's performance drew many positive responses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allkpop.com/2010/07/international-secret-agents-concert-2010-to-feature-jay-park-and-more |title=International Secret Agents Concert 2010 to feature Jay Park and more |date=July 27, 2010 |publisher=Allkpop |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allkpop.com/2010/09/a-look-back-at-isa-2010 |title=A look back at ISA 2010! |date=September 20, 2010 |publisher=Allkpop |accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPark was cast for the 2011 Korean movie ''[[Mr. Idol]]'', starring alongside friend and fellow [[SidusHQ]] actor, [[Kim Su-ro]].<ref name=\"mridol\">{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?jay_park_prepares_for_his_solo_comeback_in_korea_16509.aspx | title = Jay Park prepares for his solo comeback in Korea | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = October 3, 2011 | accessdate = June 25, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130826050022/http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?jay_park_prepares_for_his_solo_comeback_in_korea_16509.aspx | archive-date = August 26, 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Park was also one of the performers, alongside [[Seven (South Korean singer)|SE7EN]], [[Taeyang]] and [[Musiq Soulchild]], at the Seoul Soul Festival held at the War Memorial of Korea on October 10. Park and Musiq Soulchild also performed the latter's song \"[[Love (Musiq Soulchild song)|Love]]\" at the festival.<ref>{{cite news| title =Jay Park, Musiq Soulchild Perform at Seoul Soul Festival | author =Hicap, Jonathan M. | newspaper =Manila Bulletin| date = October 12, 2010 |url =http://www.mb.com.ph/node/281746/jay-park-mu | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> Park held a charity concert in December called the \"White Love Party Concert\", with [[Supreme Team (band)|Supreme Team]] and [[Dok2]] making appearances.<ref name=white-love-party-concert>{{cite web|title=Jay Park stuns 12,000 fans at \"2010 White Love Party Concert\"|url=http://www.allkpop.com/2010/12/jay-park-stuns-12000-fans-at-2010-white-love-party-concert|publisher=Allkpop via Nate|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref> Park and [[Art of Movement]] performed at \"Fever Seoul Live\" alongside [[Dumbfoundead]], [[David Choi]], and several international b-boys.<ref name=fever-seoul>{{cite web|title=Jay Park, AOM, Dumbfoundead, and David Choi Perform at \"Fever Seoul Live\"|url=http://www.soompi.com/2010/12/21/jay-park-aom-dumbfoundead-and-david-choi-perform-at-fever-seoul-live/|publisher=Soompi|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2011: ''Take a Deeper Look'' and rise as a solo artist===\nOn January 6, Park was announced as the winner in \"Best Web Video\" Category around the globe for his song \"Nothin' on You\" at the [[Mashable Awards]], and was also nominated in the \"Must Follow Personality\" category, finishing second.<ref name=\"mashableaward\">{{cite web| title =Jay Park Wins Mashables Best Web Video Award | author =Sherman, Ned | publisher =Digital Media Wire| date = January 6, 2011 |url =http://www.dmwmedia.com/news/2011/01/06/jay-park-wins-mashableaee284a2s-best-web-video-award | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> At the beginning of February, Park was featured in two music videos of girl group, [[5dolls]], called \"Lips Stains\" and \"It's You\". Park was chosen to be the sole opener for [[Ne-Yo]] in his first concert in Seoul for the \"2011 Hyundai Mall 40th Anniversary Concert\" held on March 29. He also cooperated with Ne-Yo for a charity event for children dreaming to become musicians on March 28 at the Dream Academy in Seoul.<ref name=\"neyo\">{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \ud31d\uc2a4\ud0c0 \ub2c8\uc694(NE-YO) \ub0b4\ud55c\uacf5\uc5f0 \ub2e8\ub3c5 \uc624\ud504\ub2dd \ubb34\ub300 \uc120\ub2e4 (Jay Park to appear on the opening stage for pop star Ne-Yo's Korean concert) | author= Kim, Su-Ji | publisher =bntnews | date = March 14, 2011 |url =http://bntnews.hankyung.com/apps/news?popup=0&nid=04&c1=04&c2=04&c3=00&nkey=201103141952073&mode=sub_view | accessdate = July 3, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> On March 28, Park was a finalist and received the most votes in the special category \"Connecting People Award\", a joint venture between [[Shorty Awards]] and [[Nokia]]. Park also was a finalist in the \"Celebrity\" category at the same event.<ref>{{cite web| title =Announcing the Finalists for The Connecting People Award | publisher =The Official Shorty Awards Blog| date = March 22, 2011 |url =http://blog.shortyawards.com/post/4025516977/announcing-the-finalists-for-the-connecting-people | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ParkJaeByum.jpg|thumb|left|Park during a press conference for ''Mr. Idol'' in 2011]]\nPark released his first Korean mini-album, ''[[Take a Deeper Look]]'', in April, with the lead single \"[[Abandoned (song)|Abandoned]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.nate.com/view/20110419n03571 | title = \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 \uccab \uc194\ub85c\uc568\ubc94 \uc120\uc8fc\ubb38 5\ub9cc\uc7a5 \uae30\uc5fc 'Jay-Effect' (Park Jaebeom's first solo album records 50,000 pre-orders: Jay-Effect) | author= Kim, Soo-jee | publisher = bnt news via Nate | date = April 18, 2011 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> ''Take a Deeper Look'' debuted at number three in the ''Billboard'' World Album Charts and ranked number 26 on the Billboard Heatseekers Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park's Take a Deeper Look on Billboard|url=http://mtvk.com/2011/05/05/jay-parks-take-a-deeper-look-on-billboard/|publisher=MTV K|author=Park, Anna|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> Park also made his debut as a solo artist on Korean music shows such as [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]]' ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'', [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s ''[[M! Countdown]]'', [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]'s ''[[Music Core]]'' and [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]' ''[[Inkigayo]]'', returning for the first time in two years. Park made history as the first artist crowned winner at a debut stage, as he won ''Music Bank'' on May 6 and won again a week later on May 13.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Jay's Recent Update |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=104 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715172414/http://jaypark.com/news/?p=104 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 15, 2012 |publisher=Jay Park official website |date=July 29, 2011 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 6, Park participated in his first KBS ''Immortal Songs 2'' episode, performing \"Candy\" by Korean boy band [[H.O.T.]] with its leader [[Moon Hee-joon]].<ref>{{cite web| title ='\ubd88\ud6c4\uc758 \uba85\uace12' \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94-\ubb38\ud76c\uc900 '\uce94\ub514' \uc5b4\uae68 \ub4e4\uc369\ub4e4\uc369 (Immortal Song 2: Park Jaebeom and Moon Hee-joon's \"Candy\" makes an exciting stage)| author=Pyo, Jae-min|publisher =TV Report| date = August 6, 2011 | url=http://www.tvreport.co.kr/cindex.php?c=news&m=newsview&idx=141746 |accessdate = June 29, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Park followed up with his own R&B rendition of \"Aemo\" by Kim Soo-hee on the next episode, which was well received.<ref>{{cite web| title ='\ubd88\ud6c42' \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 '\uc560\ubaa8' R&B\ud30c\uaca9\ud3b8\uace1 \"\uc2e0\uace1\uc5d0 \uc0d8\ud50c\ub9c1\ud55c \ub4ef\" (\"Immortal song 2\" Park Jaebeom sings R&B version of the song \"Affection\", \"sounds like a newest song with sampling\")| author=Jun, Won|publisher =Newsen| date = August 13, 2011 | url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201108131808511001 |accessdate = June 29, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> On his third episode of ''Immortal Songs 2'', Park performed \"Tell me the Truth\" by [[Jinusean]] with [[Solbi]], [[Jang Hyuk]] and [[Kim Su-ro]], and was the victor for that episode, allowing him to choose the order for the next episode.<ref>{{cite web | title=\ubd88\uba852 \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \ub9d0\ud574\uc918 \uc5f4\ucc3d \ucd5c\uc885\uc6b0\uc2b9 '\ub77c\uc774\ubc8c \ud6a8\ub9b0 \uc774\uacbc\ub2e4' (\"Immortal Song 2\" Park Jaebeom sings \"Tell me the truth\" and beats his rival Hyorin) | author=Im, Jae-hoon | publisher=Seoul News NTN | date=August 20, 2011 | url=http://ntn.seoul.co.kr/?c=news&m=view&idx=111720 | accessdate=June 29, 2012 | language=ko }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> For his fourth episode, Park again made his own R&B version of \"Feel Good Day\" by [[Kim Wan-sun]].<ref>{{cite web | title='\ubd88\ud6c42' \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, '\uae30\ubd84\uc88b\uc740\ub0a0' \uc5f4\ucc3d\u2026\uae40\uc644\uc120 \"\uc0c1\uc0c1\ud560 \uc218 \uc5c6\ub294 \ud3b8\uace1\" \uadf9\ucc2c (\"Immortal Song 2\" Park Jaebeom sings \"Feel Good Day\"... Kim Wan-sun compliments, \"A remix beyond imagination\") | author=Kang, Sun-ae | publisher=My Daily via Nate | date=August 27, 2011 | url=http://ntn.seoul.co.kr/?c=news&m=view&idx=111720 | accessdate=June 29, 2012 | language=ko }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On his fifth episode, Park performed a remixed version of \"Look Back at Me\" by [[Deux (band)|Deux]] with a b-boy dance break.<ref>{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \uace0\ub09c\uc774\ub3c4 \ube44\ubcf4\uc789\uc73c\ub85c '\ubd88\ud6c42' \ubb34\ub300 \uc7a5\uc545 (Park Jaebeom dominates the stage of 'Immortal Song 2' with his difficult b-boying skills)| author=Jang, Chang-hwan| publisher =Osen| date = September 3, 2011 |url =http://media.daum.net/entertain/enews/view?cateid=1032&newsid=20110903183609756&p=poctan | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> On his sixth episode and final appearance on the show, he performed \"Dear, Do Not Change\" by Nam Jin and won the trophy for his last performance,<ref>{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, '\ubd88\ud6c42' \ud558\ucc28 \uc9c1\uc804 \ucd5c\uc885 \uc6b0\uc2b9 '\uc720\uc885\uc758 \ubbf8' (Park Jaebeom wins just before he leaves 'Immortal Song 2,' bringing to a successful conclusion)| author=Baek, Sol-mi|publisher =My Daily| date = September 11, 2011 |url =http://www.mydaily.co.kr/news/read.html?newsid=201109111119331118 | accessdate = June 29, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> before leaving the show to focus on his next album's preparations.<ref>{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94\ub3c4 '\ubd88\ud6c42' \ud558\ucc28, \uc0c8\uc568\ubc94 \uc900\ube44\uc704\ud574 \ubbf8\uad6d\u884c (Park Jaebeom leaves 'Immortal Song 2' - will leave to the US for album preparation)| author=Jun, Won |publisher =Newsen| date = August 26, 2011 | url=http://news.nate.com/view/20110826n11639 |accessdate = June 29, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> It was revealed that Park would return to ''Immortal Songs 2'' for a special episode \"King of Kings\" with other singers that have claimed the number one spot. This special episode was recorded on November 7 at the KBS Open Hall and aired on November 19.<ref>{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 '\uadf8\ub300\uc5ec \ubcc0\uce58\ub9c8\uc624', \ud654\ub824\ud55c \ud37c\ud3ec\uba3c\uc2a4\ub85c \uc7ac\ud574\uc11d (Park Jaebeom reinterprets 'Dear, Please do not change' into a flashy performance)| publisher =Xportsnews| date =November 19, 2011| url =http://xportsnews.hankyung.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=201564| accessdate =June 22, 2012| language =ko| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://archive.today/20130125191005/http://xportsnews.hankyung.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=201564| archivedate =January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe single \"[[Demon (song)|Demon]]\" was released on September 5 through various Korean digital music websites.<ref>{{cite web | title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc2e0\uace1 \ub514\uba3c(Demon)\uacf5\uac1c \"\ubc29\uc1a1\ud65c\ub3d9 \uc5c6\ub2e4\" (Park Jaebeom reveals his new single, 'Demon,' \"There will be no broadcast activities\") | publisher =Billboard Korea | date =September 5, 2011 | url =http://billboard.co.kr/v1/news_view.html?t=457&i=19776#.TmRzzOmLtPE.twitter | accessdate =June 22, 2012 | language =ko | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120512025241/http://billboard.co.kr/v1/news_view.html?t=457&i=19776#.TmRzzOmLtPE.twitter | archivedate =May 12, 2012 }}</ref> The music video was also released on the same day, and Park apologized for its low quality, saying he had no control over the release of both the music video and the song.<ref>{{cite web| title =Jay Park Apologizes For \"Demon\" MV |author=Park, Anna| publisher =MTV Iggy| date = September 6, 2011 |url =http://www.mtviggy.com/blog-posts/jay-park-apologizes-for-demon-mv/ | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> \"Demon\" peaked at number 14 on the Gaon Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|title=Gaon chart|date=|publisher=Gaon|accessdate=September 10, 2011|language=ko|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CRtw7nH4?url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|archive-date=November 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and at number 8 on the iTunes R&B/Soul Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Demon\" Receives A Hot Response From US iTunes |date=September 4, 2011 |publisher=Jay Park official website |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=230 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n[[File:KoreAm 2012-01 Cover.jpg|right|thumb|Park on the cover of [[KoreAm]] for January 2012]]\n\nPark returned to the US on October 1 to perform at the International Secret Agents Los Angeles concert.<ref>{{cite web | title =2011 International Secret Agents (ISA) LA in Los Angeles | publisher =channel APA | date =September 26, 2011 | url =http://www.channelapa.com/2011/09/2011-international-secret-agents-isa-la-in-los-angeles.html | accessdate =June 22, 2012 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120515172039/http://www.channelapa.com/2011/09/2011-international-secret-agents-isa-la-in-los-angeles.html | archive-date =May 15, 2012 | url-status =dead }}</ref> On October 29, Park delivered a performance to over 25,000 fans as he headlined the [[MTV EXIT]] (End Exploitation and Trafficking) Live in Manila Concert held at the SM Mall of Asia. The concert also featured Californian alternative rock band, Evaline, and international singer-songwriter, [[Jason Mraz]].<ref>{{cite news| title =Jay Park: TADL album is my greatest achievement so far | author =Hicap, Jonathan M. | newspaper =Manila Bulletin| date = October 31, 2011 |url =http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/339603/jay-park-tadl-album-my-greatest-achievement-so-far | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPark released his single \"[[Girlfriend (Jay Park song)|Girlfriend]]\", along with the music video via his YouTube channel on November 3.<ref>{{cite web | title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc0c8 \uc2f1\uae00 '\uac78\ud504\ub80c\ub4dc(Girl Friend)' \uc2a4\ud2f8 \ucef7 \uacf5\uac1c! (Park Jaebeom's reveals a still cut from his new single, 'Girl Friend') | publisher =The Star Chosun | date =October 31, 2011 | url =http://thestar.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/10/31/2011103101942.html | accessdate =June 22, 2012 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20160127040437/http://thestar.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/10/31/2011103101942.html | archive-date =January 27, 2016 | url-status =dead }}</ref> Park performed his single on the same day at the 2011 Style Icon Awards, following a recording of tvN's Taxi.<ref>{{cite web| title ='\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc77c \uc544\uc774\ucf58' \uc7ac\ubc94 \"\ubc31\ub144 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ud074\ub798\uc2dd \uc218\ud2b8 \uc785\uc5b4\ubd24\uc5b4\uc694\" (Style icon, Park Jaebeom, \"I wore a classic suit since about a hundred years ago) | publisher =TV Report| date = November 3, 2011 |url =http://www.tvreport.co.kr/cindex.php?c=news&m=newsview&idx=167697 | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref> The movie ''[[Mr. Idol]]'' in which Park starred in was also released on November 3.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jay Park releases single 'Girlfriend' |url=http://mb.com.ph/node/340046/jay-park-relea |newspaper=Manila Bulletin |author=Hicap, Jonathan M. |date=November 4, 2011 |accessdate=June 25, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108003525/http://mb.com.ph/node/340046/jay-park-relea |archivedate=November 8, 2011 }}</ref> The single peaked at number 28 on the Gaon chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|title=Gaon chart|date=|publisher=Gaon|accessdate=November 5, 2011|language=ko|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CRtw7nH4?url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|archive-date=November 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Park released Part 1 of his first full-length Korean album, ''[[New Breed (Jay Park album)|New Breed]]'', with the lead single \"Star\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|\ubcc4}}; Revised Romanization: ''Byeol'') on December 28.<ref name=\"star\">{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc0c8 \uc2f1\uae00 '\ubcc4' \uacf5\uac1c \uc9c1\ud6c4 \uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8 \uc7a5\uc545 (Jay Park is a \"Star\" on the music charts) | author = Sin, Gyeong-jin | publisher =Nate | date = December 28, 2011 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20111228n25261 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> \"Star\" peaked at number one on various sites like Bugs, Olleh Music, and Soribada while being on the top of other charts of music sites.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Single Album New Breed PART 1 Unveiled |date=December 28, 2011 |publisher=Jay Park official website |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=285 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120709135146/http://jaypark.com/news/?p=285 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 9, 2012 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 }}</ref> The first part of ''New Breed'' also reached the top of charts of various music sites including Olleh Music, Bugs, Soribada and Daum.<ref name=\"star\" /> \"Star\" peaked at number 17 on the Gaon Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|title=Gaon chart|date=|publisher=Gaon|accessdate=December 31, 2011|language=ko|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CRtw7nH4?url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|archive-date=November 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2012: ''New Breed'' and ''Fresh Air: Breathe It''===\nPark received the Disk Bonsang for his mini album ''Take a Deeper Look'' on January 11, on the first day of the 26th [[Golden Disk Awards]], which was held in Osaka. He was the only solo artist to receive the Disk Bonsang among the other Bonsang winners.<ref name=\"gda\">{{cite web|title=The 26th Golden Disc Awards \u2013 Jay Park, The Only Solo Artist To Get Disc Award |publisher=Jay Park official website |date=January 27, 2012 |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=329 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714001612/http://jaypark.com/news/?p=329 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 14, 2012 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 }}</ref> On January 18, he received the Popular Artist Award of the Asia Model Awards, which was held in Seoul.<ref name=\"AMFA\">{{cite web|title=Winning Popularity Award at the Asia Model Festival Awards |publisher=Jay Park official website |date=February 18, 2012 |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=337 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"asiamodelawards1\">{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc5b4\ub514\uc11c\ub4e0 \uc608\uc758\ubc14\ub978 \uccad\ub144 '\uacf5\uc190\ud55c \uc218\uc0c1' (Jay Park, well-mannered young man, gives 'polite speeches') | publisher =bntnews via Nate | date = January 19, 2012 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20120119n00898 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"asiamodelawards2\">{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, \uc218\uc0c1\uc18c\uac10 \ubc1c\ud45c \uc911\uc5d0\ub3c4 \ud32c\ub4e4 \ud5a5\ud574 \ubbf8\uc18c~ (Park Jaebeom smiles towards his fans even during his thank you speech) | publisher =bntnews via Nate | date = January 19, 2012 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20120119n00950 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nSeveral songs composed and written by Park for other artists were released in 2012. Jay Park produced and composed a song with [[Cha Cha Malone]] for Korean-American singer [[Brian Joo]], titled \"Can't Stop\".<ref>{{cite web| title =\ube0c\ub77c\uc774\uc5b8, \ud0c0\uc774\uac70JK \ucc38\uc5ec\ud55c \uc2e0\uace1 '\ub108 \ub530\uc708 \ubc84\ub9ac\uace0' \uacf5\uac1c (Brian reveals his new single, 'Let This Die' featuring Tiger JK) | date = January 26, 2012 | publisher =TV Report via Nate|url =http://news.nate.com/view/20120126n15924 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"mnet1\">{{cite web | title =Can't Stop (Feat. \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94, Beenzino) | publisher =Mnet | url =http://www.mnet.com/track/2684226#info | accessdate =June 22, 2012 | language =ko | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150610222626/http://www.mnet.com/track/2684226#info | archive-date =June 10, 2015 | url-status =dead }}</ref><ref name=\"mnet2\">{{cite web | title =Can't Stop (Eng Ver.) (Feat. Jay Park, Dumbfoundead) | publisher =Mnet | url =http://www.mnet.com/track/2684225#info | accessdate =June 22, 2012 | language =ko | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120207071012/http://www.mnet.com/track/2684225#info | archive-date =February 7, 2012 | url-status =dead }}</ref> Park wrote the Korean version of the song, while Joo wrote the English Version.<ref name=\"mnet1\" /><ref name=\"mnet2\" /> Park co-wrote the song \"4U\" for the idol group [[U-Kiss]] at the request of main vocalist Soohyun, a long-time friend and fellow former [[JYP Entertainment]] trainee, and it was included in U-Kiss's sixth EP ''[[DoraDora]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=\uadf8\ub8f9 \uc720\ud0a4\uc2a4, \ud788\ud2b8 \uc791\uace1\uac00 \uae40\ud615\uc11d\uc758 \ub304\uc2a4\uace1\uc73c\ub85c \uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 \ub3c4\uc804|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2012&no=260933|newspaper=[[Maeil Business Newspaper|Maekyung Media Group]]|date=April 29, 2014|language=Korean}}</ref><ref name=\"doradora-4u\">{{cite web | title =U-KISS to Return to Korea With New Mini Album, 'Doradora' | date =April 16, 2012 | author =Ho, Stewart | publisher =CJ E&M enewsWorld | url =http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=5550 | archive-url =https://archive.today/20130129033248/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=5550 | url-status =dead | archive-date =January 29, 2013 | accessdate =July 3, 2012 }}</ref> Park also produced and composed a song for the girl group [[Tiny-G]], entitled \"Polaris\"; the lyrics were written by actress [[Lee Si-young]]. They worked together through MBC's ''Music and Lyrics''.<ref>{{cite web| title =Cast picked for music reality show | publisher =Korea Joongang Daily | date = April 14, 2012 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20111228n25261 | accessdate = June 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title =\uc774\uc2dc\uc601\uc791\uc0ac\u2022\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 \uc791\uace1, \ud0c0\uc774\ub2c8\uc9c0 \uc74c\uc6d0 \uacf5\uac1c (Tiny G releases song with Lee Si Young as lyricist and Park Jaebeom as composer) | newspaper =Starnews | date = May 4, 2012 |url =http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2012050417273248431&type=3 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> On July 3, Korean pop singer [[Younha]] released her fourth Korean album, ''[[Supersonic (Younha album)|Supersonic]]'', including the track \"Driver\" written by Park. He also featured in the song, providing rap verses.<ref name=younha>{{cite web | title =Younha's Fourth Album to Include Jay Park, Tiger JK, John Park and More | author =Ho, Stewart | publisher =CJ E&M enewsWorld | date =June 26, 2012 | url =http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=8610&idxType=News&trendKeyword=Jay%20Park | accessdate =July 3, 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<!---[[File:Jay Park performing shirtless.jpg|thumb|left|Park performing at the [[Jecheon]] International Music & Film Festival, 2012]]--->\nHe released his first full-length Korean album, ''[[New Breed (Jay Park album)|New Breed]]'', in February, with the lead single \"Know Your Name\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park, Unveils Full Album Title Song! \"Know Your Name\" Music Video Teaser Release |date=February 18, 2012 |publisher=Jay Park official website |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=361 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414162222/http://jaypark.com/news/?p=361 |archivedate=April 14, 2012 }}</ref> The album reached number 1 twice on the Gaon Weekly album chart in South Korea,<ref name=\"week1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|title=Gaon Weekly album chart|date=February 11, 2012|publisher=Gaon|accessdate=February 11, 2012|language=ko|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CRtw7nH4?url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|archive-date=November 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"week2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|title=Gaon Weekly album chart|date=February 25, 2012|publisher=Gaon|accessdate=February 25, 2012|language=ko|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6CRtw7nH4?url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/album/list.gaon|archive-date=November 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and also reached number 1 on the Hanteo Weekly chart by selling more than 80,000 copies offline in 10 days.<ref name=\"hanteo\" /><ref name=\"hanteo2\">{{cite web| title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 'New Breed', \ud55c\ud130\ucc28\ud2b8 \uc8fc\uac04 1\uc704 '\uc6b0\ub69d' (Park Jaebeom's 'New Breed' stands at No. 1 on the Hanteo Weekly Chart) | date = February 29, 2012 | publisher =Etoday|url =http://www.etoday.co.kr/news/section/newsview.php?TM=news&SM=4101&idxno=551466 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> ''New Breed'' debuted at number 4 on the ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'' World Album Charts and ranked number 16 on the ''Billboard'' Heatseekers Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Full Album 'New Breed' On US Billboard Charts |date=April 9, 2012 |publisher=Jay Park official website |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=385 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414162233/http://jaypark.com/news/?p=385 |archivedate=April 14, 2012 }}</ref> Park made his comeback stage on Korean music shows on February 16. He won ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'' on February 24, one week after his comeback.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park Proves Popularity By Topping Charts 1 Week After Comeback |date=April 9, 2012 |publisher=Jay Park official website |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=392 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414162402/http://jaypark.com/news/?p=392 |archivedate=April 14, 2012 }}</ref> On April 27, Park began Asian promotions for the Asian version release of his album ''New Breed'', and visited 5 countries: [[Singapore]], [[Philippines|the Philippines]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]] and Japan. On April 28, Jay performed at the 2012 [[Star Awards 2012|Star Awards]] in Singapore.<ref name=\"asianpromotions\" /> On June 13, he released the Japan editions of his albums ''Take a Deeper Look'' and ''New Breed'' through [[Universal J]]. The regular edition of ''New Breed'' includes the English version of \"I Love You\" and the acoustic version of \"Know Your Name\" as bonus tracks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park - Universal Music Japan |publisher=Jay Park Universal Music Japan Website |url=http://beta.universal-music.co.jp/jaypark |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120708203430/http://beta.universal-music.co.jp/jaypark |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2012 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nJay Park held his first solo concert, ''New Breed Live in Seoul'', on March 3 at the Olympic Hall of [[Olympic Park, Seoul|Seoul Olympic Park]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park First Solo Concert, Sold Out in 10 Minutes |date=April 9, 2012 |publisher=Jay Park official website |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=388 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414162358/http://jaypark.com/news/?p=388 |archivedate=April 14, 2012 }}</ref> Park successfully held a second concert ''New Breed Asia Tour in Seoul'' in Seoul on August 18 at the Olympic Hall of Seoul Olympic Park, and unlike the first, which was held in March, this one did not have a 19+ age restriction.<ref>{{cite web | title =Jay Park to Embark on Asia Concert Tour | author =Ho, Stewart | publisher =CJ E&M enewsWorld | date =June 15, 2012 | url =http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=8008&idxType=News&trendKeyword=Jay%20Park | accessdate =July 3, 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Park was selected as the 2012 [[R-16 Korea]] ambassador by the [[Korea Tourism Organization]] on April 23.<ref name=\"asianpromotions\">{{cite web|title=Jay Park, Shooting Stars in Asia's Skies-'New Breed' Asian Promotion starting April 27th |date=April 26, 2012 |publisher=Jay Park official website |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=409 |accessdate=June 22, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nHe headlined the [[APAHM]] tour organized by [[Verizon]] in the US in May, including concerts in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[New York City]], [[San Francisco]] and [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Jay Park Wraps Up Successful Concert Tour in America | author = Ho, Stewart | publisher = CJ E&M enewsWorld | date = June 7, 2012 | url = http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=7615 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130130010343/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=7615 | url-status = dead | archive-date = January 30, 2013 | accessdate = July 3, 2012 }}</ref> On May 16, Park released his first [[mixtape]], ''[[Fresh A!r: Breathe !t]]'',<ref>{{cite web | title =Jay Park Releases Free Special Mixtape for Fans | author =Ho, Stewart | publisher =CJ E&M enewsWorld | date =May 17, 2012 | url =http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=6817 | archive-url =https://archive.today/20130128225948/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=6817 | url-status =dead | archive-date =January 28, 2013 | accessdate =July 3, 2012 }}</ref> containing songs he performed for the tour.<ref>{{cite web| title =\uc7ac\ubc94, \ud32c\ub4e4 \uc704\ud574 6\uace1 \ubb34\ub8cc\ub85c \uc804\uc138\uacc4 \uacf5\uac1c (Jaebeom internationally releases 6 songs dedicated to his fans for free) | author = Gang, Seung-hun | publisher =TV Report | date = May 17, 2012 |url =http://tvreport.co.kr/cindex.php?c=news&m=newsview&idx=227175 | accessdate = June 22, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> The mixtape was certified Gold by Datpiff within a month since its release, meaning it was downloaded over 100,000 times. Jay Park became the first artist of Asian origin to achieve this result on Datpiff.<ref>{{cite web | title = Jay Park First Asian Artist Recognized by America's Largest Mixtape Site | author = Ho, Stewart | publisher = CJ E&M enewsWorld | date = July 16, 2012 | url = http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=10313&idxType=News | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130129054024/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=10313&idxType=News | url-status = dead | archive-date = January 29, 2013 | accessdate = September 7, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<!---->\nPark was the closing act at the [[MTV World Stage Live in Malaysia]], along with Canadian pop singer [[Justin Bieber]], Korean girl band [[Kara (South Korean band)|Kara]], and Malaysian singer [[Mizz Nina]], on July 14. Park also performed his song \"Carefree\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Jay Park unveils new song at MTV concert in Malaysia |author=Hicap, Jonathan M. |newspaper=Manila Bulletin |date=July 16, 2012 |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/366140/jay-park-unveils-new-song-mtv-concert-malaysia |accessdate=July 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717181357/http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/366140/jay-park-unveils-new-song-mtv-concert-malaysia |archivedate=July 17, 2012 }}</ref> which was included on the ''New Breed Red Edition'' repackaged album, and also showed his self-choreographed dance break to \"[[Dirty Bass (song)|Dirty Bass]]\" by [[Far East Movement]] featuring [[Tyga]],<ref name=mtv-world-stage-bieber-upstaged>{{cite news|title=Bieber upstaged by Jay Park|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Showbiz/Story/A1Story20120716-359442.html|author = Rasul, Juliana June | date =July 18, 2012| newspaper=The New Paper|accessdate=September 5, 2012}}</ref> which he later shared on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web |title = Jay Park Dances with Prepix Crew with Self-Created Choreography |author = Dong, Grace Danbi |url = http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=11037&idxType=News |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130129140346/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=11037&idxType=News |url-status = dead |archive-date = January 29, 2013 |publisher = CJ E&M enewsWorld |date = July 30, 2012 |accessdate = September 5, 2012 }}</ref> Park also held his own concerts in Sydney and Melbourne at the end of September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park Australia Tour 2012 |author = Chong, Carene | url=http://www.meldmagazine.com.au/2012/07/jay-park-australia-tour-2012/|publisher=Meld Magazine|date = July 13, 2012 | accessdate=September 5, 2012}}</ref> Also in July, Park started a [[web series]], ''[[Jay Park TV]]'', through his YouTube channel, filmed and edited by Hep, Park's friend and fellow [[Art of Movement]] member.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allkpop.com/2012/07/jay-park-reveals-1st-jay-park-tv-youtube-webisode |title=Jay Park reveals 1st ''Jay Park TV'' Youtube webisode |date=July 23, 2012 |publisher=Allkpop |accessdate=August 25, 2012}}</ref> The web series shows Park's daily life with his friends, behind-the-scenes of concerts and filming, and the fun and games that he gets up to.\n\nIn August, Jay Park released a music video for \"New Breed\", from the album of the same name, which was recorded during the album's photo shoot with Park featuring [[Rick Genest]]-inspired make-up.<ref name=newbreed-mv>{{cite web|title=NEW BREED|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2n-5lRKnE_U|publisher=Jay Park|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref> Park also uploaded a practice video to \"I Love You\", showing the complex choreography that he and Prepix members were practising for his upcoming concert.<ref name=iloveyou-practice>{{cite web|title=I LOVE YOU PRACTICE|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_sSpHX6zR8|publisher=Jay Park|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref> On August 22, Park was announced to be a fixed panel member on MBC's ''Come to Play'', along with Kim Eung-soo and [[Kwon Oh-joong]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park Joins Revamped MBC's 'Come to Play' As Fixed Panelist | url=http://www.allkpop.com/2012/08/jay-park-kim-eung-soo-and-kwon-oh-joon-become-newest-panel-members-on-come-to-play|publisher=allkpop|date = August 22, 2012 | accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref> He joined as a part of a new corner on the show, titled the \"Trueman Show\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Jay Park Joins Revamped MBC's 'Come to Play' As Fixed Panelist |author = Ho, Stewart |url = http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=13145 |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130128214947/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=13145 |url-status = dead |archive-date = January 28, 2013 |publisher = CJ E&M enewsWorld |date = August 23, 2012 |accessdate = September 7, 2012 }}</ref> MBC suddenly axed the show after several months, with no prior warning to the cast nor producers.\n\nLater in September, Park performed for the first time in Australia, successfully holding concerts in [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]].<ref name=meld-magazine>{{cite web|title=Jay Park Australia Tour 2012|url=http://www.meldmagazine.com.au/2012/07/jay-park-australia-tour-2012/|publisher=meld magazine|accessdate=February 24, 2013|date=July 13, 2012}}</ref> Park returned to ''Immortal Songs 2'' for a \"King of Kings\" special in October, where he performed \"The Woman in Rain\" by [[Shin Jung-hyeon]]. In a flying visit to [[Los Angeles]], Jay Park made a last-minute appearance in a YouTube sketch by [[David So]], which parodies [[Wong Fu Productions]]' ''The Last''.<ref name=the-last-resort>{{cite web|title=The Last Resort|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QQMf3DaBdk8|publisher=David So|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November, he featured on \"If You Love Me\", a digital single by [[NS Yoon-G]]. Although Park does not make an appearance in the official music video, he performed on stage with Yoon-G on music shows, with the first being [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s [[M! Countdown]], and also makes an appearance in the behind-the-scenes music video, showing NS Yoon-G and Park in the studio recording the song.<ref name=mnet-if-you-love-me>{{cite web|title=NS\uc724\uc9c0&\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94_If you love me(If you love me by NS YoonG & Jay Park @Mcountdown 2012.11.01)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k0eW-RS3zDM|publisher=Mnet|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref> A practice video of the choreography was released soon after.<ref name=if-you-love-me-practice>{{cite web|title=NS Yoon-G, (NS\uc724\uc9c0) - If You Love Me feat. Jay Park \uc548\ubb34\uc601\uc0c1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wKw6oR_q5Ys|publisher=NS Yoon-G|accessdate=February 24, 2013}}</ref>\nPark was the host of the December 1 episode of [[Saturday Night Live Korea]], garnering attention for his R-rated skits, acting, and a parody music video of [[Eminem]]'s [[Love the Way You Lie]], bringing in the highest ratings of the season for the show.<ref name=snl-mnet>{{cite web|title=Jay Park Brings High Ratings to \"SNL Korea\"|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=22811|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129052750/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=22811|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 29, 2013|publisher=mnet|accessdate=December 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2013: \"Joah\", ''SNL Korea'', and launch of hip hop label, AOMG===\nOn January 18, Park held a showcase in [[Singapore]], making the [[city-state]] the location in which he has held the most performances, after Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park performs in Singapore 2013|url=http://sg.entertainment.yahoo.com/blogs/singapore-showbiz/jay-park-just-boy-hood-060704061.html|publisher=Yahoo SG|accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref> In Singapore, Park gave an interview with his fansite, ''Jay Park Network'', revealing he would be shooting 11 music videos this year, and gave a short teaser of an upcoming single.<ref name=jpnet-interview-singapre>{{cite web|title=170113 Jay Park Network Interviews Jay Park|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gOlQy5ZxkwM|publisher=Jay Park Network|accessdate=March 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jay Park at Korean Music Awards in 2013-2.jpg|thumb|left|Park accepting the award for Musician of the Year at the [[Korean Music Awards]], 2013]]\nOn February 6, it was announced that Park will be joining the cast of ''[[Saturday Night Live Korea]]'', having previously hosted an episode in late 2012.<ref name=snl-korea-2013-announcement>{{cite web|title=Jay Park to Join \"Saturday Night Live Korea\"|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=28586|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130419003801/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=28586|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 19, 2013|publisher=mnet|accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref> On [[Valentine's Day]], February 14, Park released a song and music video, \"Appetizer\", available for free download on [[SoundCloud]],<ref name=appetizer-soundcloud>{{cite web|title=JAY PARK - Appetizer|url=http://soundcloud.com/jayparkaom-1/jay-park-2013-appetizer|publisher=Jay Park|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref> produced by friend and fellow [[Art of Movement]] member, [[Cha Cha Malone]].<ref name=appetizer-mnet>{{cite web|title=[Video] Jay Park Drops '2013 Appetizer' and Gifts Fans with Free Servings|url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=29163|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130419011443/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/enews/contents.asp?idx=29163|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 19, 2013|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name=appetizer-youtube>{{cite web|title=JAY PARK - 2013 APPETIZER ( PROD. BY CHA CHA MALONE )|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_PCNfXw8Ldc|publisher=Jay Park|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref> On the first episode of ''Saturday Night Live Korea'', Park garnered attention for his skit parodying the film ''[[:ko:\ud640\ub9ac\ub370\uc774|Holiday]]'' with Korean actor and host of the episode, [[Choi Min-soo]], and for his [[ad lib]] during a skit with [[Shin Dong-yup (entertainer)|Shin Dong-yup]] and [[Kim Seul-gi]] which ended up with the cast trying to hold in their laughter.<ref name=snl-first-ep-choi-min-soo>{{cite web|title='SNL' Choi Min Soo lets loose... a love confession for Jay Park?|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20130224n00421|publisher=E-Today via Nate|accessdate=May 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name=snl-adlib-first-ep>{{cite web|title='SNL' Shin Dong Yub laughs out loud at Jay Park's adlib 'prone to NG'|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&oid=109&aid=0002487317&sid1=001|publisher=Osen via [[Naver]]|accessdate=May 3, 2013}}</ref> In mid-February, [[Mizz Nina]]'s single, \"Around the World\", which is written by and features Park, and produced by Cha Cha Malone, was played on [[hitz.fm]] before public release. The single was officially released on February 25, and had been in the works since Park and Mizz Nina performed at [[MTV World Stage Live in Malaysia|MTV World Stage Live in Malaysia 2012]].<ref name=mtvasia-around-the-world>{{cite web|title=Mizz Nina And Jay Park Go 'Around The World'|url=http://www.mtvasia.com/news/mizz-nina-and-jay-park-go-around-the-world?xrs=share_twitter#.US8BfpEH--4.twitter|publisher=MTVasia|accessdate=February 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=itunes-around-the-world>{{cite web|title=Around the World (feat. Jay Park) - Single|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/around-world-feat.-jay-park/id608425051|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=February 28, 2013}}</ref> On February 28, Park received the \"Musician of the Year\" award at the 2013 [[Korean Music Awards]], and his 2012 album, ''[[New Breed (Jay Park album)|New Breed]]'', was nominated in the \"Best R&B and Soul album\" category.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buskers, Jay Park, Lena Park, popular music award netizens Award|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2013&no=133774|publisher=mk.co.kr|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref><ref name=kma-award-received>{{cite web|title=Jay Park receives \"Musician of the Year\" award at Korean Music Awards 2013|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1109549801|publisher=Osen|accessdate=February 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJay Park featured on the cover of the March edition of ''[[Men's Health (magazine)|Men's Health Korea]]'' magazine, and the cover was subsequently chosen by staff as the best in the magazine's 7-year history.<ref name=mens-health-tweet>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Yoojin|title=7th anni. Men's Health cover is evaluated the best cover in their 7 year history by MH staffs!|url=https://www.twitter.com/GGoingGGoing/status/304087688322093056|publisher=Yoojin Lee|accessdate=February 21, 2013}}</ref> On March 25, Park uploaded the 5th episode of ''[[Jay Park TV]]'' to his YouTube channel.<ref name=jaypark-tv-ep5>{{cite web|title=Jay Park TV Ep. 05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x9Fko0Z6ZnQ|publisher=Jay Park|accessdate=March 25, 2013}}</ref> On March 26, the music video for Mizz Nina's \"Around The World\", featuring Park, was released, and was filmed in [[South Korea]] in December 2012.<ref name=around-the-world-mv>{{cite web|title=Mizz Nina feat. Jay Park - Around the World (Official Music Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L6DjJvxbEfk|publisher=Mizz Nina|accessdate=March 26, 2013}}</ref> On March 28, it was revealed that Park would be rejoining the cast of KBS' ''[[Saturday Freedom#Immortal Songs 2|Immortal Songs 2]]'' for a third time, with the first episode featuring Park airing on April 20.<ref name=rejoining-is2-april-2013>{{cite web|title=Park to rejoin Immortal Song 2 in April 2013|url=http://m.tvreport.co.kr/view.php?m1=1&idx=326786|publisher=tvreport|accessdate=April 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215205059/http://m.tvreport.co.kr/view.php?m1=1&idx=326786|archive-date=February 15, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFollowing on from the success of the Jay Park's March edition of ''Men's Health Korea'', the same cover was used for the April edition of ''Men's Health China'', which was also the magazine's 10th anniversary edition, and included large promotional posters across the country.<ref name=mens-health-china-1>{{cite web|title=Men's Health Weibo|url=http://media.weibo.com/profile.php?uid=mhchina|publisher=Men's Health China|accessdate=April 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514184252/http://media.weibo.com/profile.php?uid=mhchina|archive-date=May 14, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=mens-health-china-10-year>{{cite web|last=Yunyun|first=Xu|title=Men's Health China 10 years old!|url=http://www.mhtrends.com.cn/master/?Men/detail/id/1212/tid/3.html|publisher=Men's Health China|accessdate=April 11, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615051651/http://www.mhtrends.com.cn/master/?Men/detail/id/1212/tid/3.html|archivedate=June 15, 2013}}</ref> In collaboration with [[Ustream|Ustream Korea]], Park held an official livestreamed event titled \"Fan & Music Live\" on April 2,<ref name=ustream-event-2013>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Jay|title=Official Jay Park Ustream|url=http://www.ustream.tv/recorded/30776323|publisher=Ustream|accessdate=April 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215204950/http://www.ustream.tv/recorded/30776323|archive-date=February 15, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and revealed the titles of the 3 songs from his upcoming single; \"[[Joah (song)|Joah]]\" ({{lang-ko|\uc88b\uc544}}; [[Revised Romanization of Korean|Revised Romanization]]: ''Joha''), \"1 Hunnit\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|\uc0ac\uc2e4\uc774\uc57c}}; Revised Romanization: ''Sasiriya''), and \"Welcome\". The title track, \"[[Joah (song)|Joah]]\", was revealed to be a mellow feel-good song similar to \"[[Girlfriend (Jay Park song)|Girlfriend]]\" produced by Cha Cha Malone and instrumentals by ''Saturday Night Live Korea'' in-session band Common Ground, \"1 Hunnit\" a rap track featuring [[Dok2]], and \"Welcome\" a sexy and provocative [[R&B]] track.<ref name=\"ustream-revealed-info\">See [http://www.ustream.tv/recorded/30776323 recorded Ustream broadcast] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215204950/http://www.ustream.tv/recorded/30776323 |date=February 15, 2015 }}</ref> On April 5, Park released the music video of \"1 Hunnit\" on his YouTube Channel, featuring Dok2 and a variety of Park's friends, including dancers and b-boys.<ref name=jay-park-1hunnit-mv>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Jay|title=JAY PARK FT. DOK2 - \uc0ac\uc2e4\uc774\uc57c (1HUNNIT) PROD. BY LODEF (OFFICIAL M/V)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jVE3qq9MCyc|publisher=Jay Park|accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> On April 9, Park appeared on [[TVN (Southeast Asia)|tvN]]'s ''Taxi'' with fellow ''Saturday Night Live Korea'' cast member, [[:ko:\uae40\uc2ac\uae30 (\ubc30\uc6b0)|Kim Seul-gi]].<ref name=tvn-taxi-2013>{{cite web|last=Hong|first=Grace Danbi|title=Jay Park on ''Taxi'' with Kim Seul-gi|url=http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=33469&idxType=News&trendKeyword=Jay%20Park|publisher=CJ E&M enewsWorld|accessdate=April 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610015836/http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=33469&idxType=News&trendKeyword=Jay%20Park|archive-date=June 10, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> On April 10, Park released his single album \"[[Joah (song)|Joah]]\", along with the music video for the title track.<ref name=joah-enewsmnet>{{cite web|last=Hong|first=Grace Danbi|title=Jay Park JOAHs Everything about You and Seattle|url=http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=33583&idxType=News&trendKeyword=Jay%20Park|publisher=CJ E&M enewsWorld|accessdate=April 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610080208/http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=33583&idxType=News&trendKeyword=Jay%20Park|archive-date=June 10, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The feel-good song features an upbeat melody with the music video filmed in Park's hometown of [[Seattle]] earlier in the year starring Korean actress [[:ko:\uc774\uc131\ubbfc (\uc5ec\uc790 \ubc30\uc6b0)|Clara Lee]].<ref name=joah-enewsmnet /><ref>{{cite web|last=Hong|first=Grace Danbi|title=Jay Park Reveals MV Teaser for \u2032JOAH\u2032 with Clara|url=http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=32695&idxType=News|publisher=CJ E&M enewsWorld|date=March 29, 2013|accessdate=April 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402005156/http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=32695&idxType=News|archive-date=April 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Members of Park's b-boy crew, [[Art of Movement]], also feature in the music video, including a short scene at The Beacon, the dance studio of fellow Seattle-based b-boy crew, [[Massive Monkees]].<ref name=\"joah-mv-info\">See [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rMtCJC39SqU JAY PARK - JOAH (\uc88b\uc544) (OFFICIAL M/V)]</ref> On April 16, Park appeared on [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]' ''[[Hwasin \u2013 Controller of the Heart]]'', the sequel of ''[[Strong Heart (TV series)|Strong Heart]]''. On the April 20 episode of Immortal Songs 2, Park sang [[Sim Soo-bong]]'s \"Men Are Ships, Women Are Harbors\". On the April 20 episode on ''Saturday Night Live'', Park's digital short with host and singer, [[Lee Soo-young]], parodied American rapper [[Jay-Z]]'s \"[[Run This Town]]\", and received attention due to scenes with Park dressed in a bikini.<ref name=snl-lee-soo-young>{{cite web|title='SNL Korea' Jay Park, bikini challenge makes the viewers laugh|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20130420n14948|publisher=TV Report via Nate|accessdate=May 3, 2013}}</ref> On April 25, Park's 26th birthday, Park released a music video for \"Welcome\" on his YouTube channel. The [[Korea Media Rating Board|19+]] video starred [[:ko:\uc624\ucd08\ud76c|Oh Cho-hee]] opposite Park, who garnered attention himself due to the shirtless and sensual scenes.<ref name=welcome-mv-yt>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Jay|title=\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 Jay Park 'Welcome' [Official Music Video]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wg26NlzPvmQ|publisher=Jay Park}}</ref> Immediately after the release of the music video, attention was drawn to various female models and actresses that have starred in all of Park's previous music videos. Also on April 25, the [[DVD]], ''New Breed Live in Seoul'', of Park's 2012 concerts was released. He performed [[:ko:\uc774\ubb38\uc138|Lee Moon-sae]]'s \"Sunset Glow\" with friend and R&B singer Crush of VV:D on the April 27 episode of ''Immortal Songs 2''.<ref name=is2-27-april>{{cite web|author=Johnelle|title=5 Things I LOVED in K-pop: 4/22 \u2013 4/28|url=http://seoulbeats.com/2013/04/5-things-i-loved-in-k-pop-422-428/|publisher=seoulbeats|accessdate=May 3, 2013}}</ref> Park's skit on the April 27 episode of ''Saturday Night Live'' with [[Gayoon]] of [[4Minute]] gained attention for Park's character mistakenly saying inappropriate and sexual words in Korean, and featured a return of Park's in-character ad lib as the camera's failed to cut away at the end of the skit.<ref name=snl-4minute-adlib>{{cite web|last=Hong|first=Grace Danbi|title=Jay Park Hilariously Handles Live Broadcast Accident|url=http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=35003&idxType=News|publisher=CJ E&M enewsWorld|accessdate=May 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606165216/http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=35003&idxType=News|archive-date=June 6, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 3, it was revealed that Park will be participating in the [[soundtrack]] of [[M. Night Shyamalan]]'s 2013 American [[science-fiction film|science-fiction]] [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] film, ''[[After Earth]]'', having been personally contacted by [[Will Smith]] and [[Jaden Smith]].<ref name=after-earth-enewsworld>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Erika|title=Jay Park to Sing Self-Written Song for Will Smith\u2032s \u2032After Earth\u2032|url=http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=35320|publisher=CJ E&M enewsWorld|accessdate=May 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525050004/http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=35320|archive-date=May 25, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The song, titled \"I Like 2 Party\", is intended for the ending theme of the film and is written and composed by Park himself, and produced by friend and fellow [[Art of Movement]] member, [[Cha Cha Malone]].<ref name=after-earth-korea-com>{{cite web|title=Jay Park joins in the making of the sound track for the American movie After Earth |url=http://en.korea.com/blog/enter/k-pop/jay-park-joins-in-the-making-of-the-sound-track-for-the-american-movie-after-earth |publisher=Star news via Korea.com |accessdate=May 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508130530/http://en.korea.com/blog/enter/k-pop/jay-park-joins-in-the-making-of-the-sound-track-for-the-american-movie-after-earth/ |archivedate= May 8, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=after-earth-cha-cha-i-like-to-party>{{cite web|last=Malone|first=Chase|title=\"I Like To Party\" produced by Cha Cha Malone|url=https://www.twitter.com/ChaChaAOM/status/330268230935535617|publisher=[[Twitter]] / [[Cha Cha Malone]]|accessdate=May 3, 2013}}</ref> During the same week, Park was announced to be the official ambassador of international [[b-boy]] tournament and cultural festival, [[R-16 Korea]], for the third year in a row.<ref name=r-16-2013-tweet>{{cite web|title=Today @JAYBUMAOM has been nominated as R16 2013 Ambassador!|url=https://www.twitter.com/R16KOREA/status/331024702489366529|publisher=[[R-16 Korea]]|accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name=r16-2013-jay-tweet>{{cite web|title=Jay Park is rocking wit R16 once again for the third year in a row!!|url=https://www.twitter.com/JAYBUMAOM/status/330895753125953536|publisher=Jay Park / Twitter|accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> Park released a 30-second snippet of \"I Like 2 Party\" with a short trailer of ''[[After Earth]]'' that day.<ref name=iliketoparty-snippet>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Jay|title=AFTER EARTH MOVIE TRAILER WITH I LIKE TO PARTY SNIPPET|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ldmI0fP9bYY|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=May 5, 2013}}</ref> On May 7, Park attended the ''After Earth'' red carpet premiere in Korea along with Will and Jaden Smith.<ref name=koream-after-earth>{{cite web|last=Hawkins |first=Chelsea |title=Will Smith Taps Jay Park Song For 'After Earth' Korean Soundtrack |url=http://iamkoream.com/will-smith-taps-jay-park-song-for-after-earth-korean-soundtrack/ |publisher=[[KoreAm]] |accessdate=July 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709220552/http://iamkoream.com/will-smith-taps-jay-park-song-for-after-earth-korean-soundtrack/ |archivedate= July 9, 2013 }}</ref> On May 11, ''Immortal Songs 2'''s 100th episode, Park performed \"Everyday Day With You\" by Deulgukhwa, remixed with Park's latest single, \"[[Joah (song)|Joah]]\", impressing the audience with his singing ability even after dancing and [[tumbling (gymnastics)|tumbling]] on stage.<ref name=is2-every-day-with-you>{{cite web|title=Jay Park - Every Day With You|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9cBIuW77MYY|accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> Later that month, Jay made a guest appearance at [[Mizz Nina]]'s concert in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]], where they performed their hit single, \"Around the World\" for the first time.<ref name=atw-concert-malaysia>{{cite news|last=Chua |first=Dennis |title=Around The World with Mizz Nina |url=http://www.nst.com.my/life-times/showbiz/around-the-world-with-mizz-nina-1.280467 |newspaper=[[New Straits Times]] |accessdate=July 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709125117/http://www.nst.com.my/life-times/showbiz/around-the-world-with-mizz-nina-1.280467 |archivedate= July 9, 2013 }}</ref> Although not in Korea for the live broadcast, Park's pre-recorded [[practical joke|shenanigans]] in a skit with [[Jason Mraz]] on the May 18 episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live Korea]]'' drew attention from viewers of the late-night sketch comedy show. Two days after this event, Park appeared on ''[[Let's Go Dream Team! Season 2]]'' and travelled to [[Singapore]] to launch a collaboration between himself and local capsule speaker company, X-mini.<ref name=cnet-x-mini>{{cite web|last=Low |first=Aloysius |title=K-pop star Jay Park launches special edition X-mini speaker |url=http://asia.cnet.com/k-pop-star-jay-park-launches-special-edition-x-mini-speaker-62221440.htm |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=July 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608054255/http://asia.cnet.com/k-pop-star-jay-park-launches-special-edition-x-mini-speaker-62221440.htm |archivedate= June 8, 2013 }}</ref> Following these events, on May 30, a song for [[Korean drama]], ''She is Wow'' titled \"Rude Girl\", by [[Kim Seul-gi]] and Park was released with a music video.<ref name=she-is-wow-ost>{{cite web|title=Rude Girl - Kim Seul-gie with Jay Park|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H8lDtsJ1TIY|publisher=[[CJ E&M Music and Live]]|accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nInformation regarding the official anthem of [[R-16 Korea]], \"Respect 16\", along with the music video to be filmed live during the 2013 international [[b-boy]] event was released on June 17 by Park.<ref name=Respect-16>{{cite web|title=The Ambassador of R16 makes the official R16 anthem:\"Respect 16\"|url=http://www.r16korea.com/xe/blog_2011_en/61025|publisher=[[R-16 Korea]]|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The next day, Park released the sixth episode of ''[[Jay Park TV]]'', showing behind the scenes of filming for television shows, photo shoots, and the music video of his single \"[[Joah (song)|Joah]]\".<ref name=jptv-ep-6>{{cite web|title=\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 Jay Park TV [Episode 6]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EnB5R_tCOVE|publisher=Jay Park|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJay Park renewed his contract with [[SidusHQ]] early in July, after much public speculation of him signing with other labels. He was to perform at the [[Hennessy]] Artistry event early in July in [[Guangzhou]], China, alongside [[B.o.B]], but the event was cancelled at the last moment due to technical difficulties.<ref name=guangzhou-event-cancelled>{{cite web|title=I regret to tell everyone that today's show was cancelled...|url=http://www.weibo.com/2685526717/zELQeDv6S|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> On July 10, Park released a four-track [[Extended play|EP]], ''I Like 2 Party'', containing the songs \"I Like 2 Party\", \"Hot\", \"Secret\" and \"Let's Make Up\", and also released a music video for the title track \"I Like 2 Party\" which was filmed in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=ilike2party-itunes>{{cite web|title=I Like 2 Party - EP|url=https://itunes.apple.com/album/i-like-2-party-ep/id670880583|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=ilike2party-yt>{{cite web|title=\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 Jay Park 'I Like 2 Party' Official Music Video [AOMG]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SpkHmgnWx_U|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> On November 30, Park served as the emcee for the [[BC One|Red Bull BC One]].\n\n=== 2014\u2013present: Growth of AOMG and ''Evolution'' ===\nIn April 2014, Park was chosen as a dance master for Season 2 of ''Dancing 9'', a Korean dance competition show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2014/04/02/jay-park-joins-dancing-9-season-2-as-a-dance-master/#.U0uKTPmqlOI|title=Jay Park Joins \"Dancing 9 Season 2\" as a Dance Master - Soompi|website=www.soompi.com}}</ref> Park's team on Dancing nine the blue eye won that season. In September 1, 2014, his second full-length album came out called Evolution. Evolution holds 17 songs, including a remix of his single release after New Breed and new tracks. Jay Park participated as a judge on Mnet's Show Me the Money 4. In 2015 he released an extensive list of songs including \"Lotto\", \"All I Got Time For\", \"On It\", \"Want It\", \"Mommae\" and \"Sex Trip\". He released \"My Last\" featuring LOCO and Gray in July 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=My Last|url=http://www.soompi.com/2015/07/14/jay-park-to-drop-new-summer-love-song-my-last-featuring-loco-and-gray/|website=Soompi|accessdate= July 20, 2015}}</ref> Jay Park released his album ''WORLDWIDE'' in November 2015.<ref name=\"Worldwide\"/> In March 2016 Jay Park released a new song titled \"The Truth Is\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Truth Is|url=http://www.soompi.com/2016/03/21/jay-park-is-ready-to-hit-the-streets-in-dazed-and-confused/|website=Soompi|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> In 2014 Jay Park took part in a small number of episodes of ''America's Next Top Model'', cycle 21, which was filmed earlier that year in Seoul.\n\nOn November 5, 2015, Jay Park released the studio album ''Worldwide'', including the lead single \"You Know (\ubed4\ud558\uc796\uc544)\" featuring Okasian and produced by Cha Cha Malone. The music video stars 4Minute's HyunA, Reddy, and Ugly Duck among others, and was directed by the production company Tiger Cave. ''Worldwide'' included a total of 18 tracks and featured 27 artists. The album was available online and as a physical release. The album also debuted at number five on ''Billboard''{{'}}s World Albums chart. Jay Park also released music videos for tracks \"Bo$$\", \"Worldwide x Want It\" and \"In this B*tch x My\".\n\nOn October 20, 2016, Jay Park released the album ''Everything You Wanted'' with a total of 19 tracks both in English and Korean. Upon release the album debuted at number three on ''Billboard''{{'}}s World Albums chart.\n\nOn October 21, 2016, Far East Movement released their album ''Identity'' including the track \"SXWME\", which features [[MNEK]] and Jay Park.\n\nIt was announced on July 20, 2017 that Roc Nation had signed Park for his activities in the US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7873936/jay-park-roc-nation-signed|title=Jay Park Signs With Roc Nation: 'This Is a Win for Asian Americans'|work=Billboard|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref> On July 27, 2017, it was announced that he will be the new judge, replacing [[Melanie C]] and [[Vanness Wu]], on the second season of ''[[Asia's Got Talent]]'' alongside [[Anggun]] and [[David Foster]]. In 2017, Park also founded H1ghr Music with producer Cha Cha Malone. Currently, the label houses South Korean and American artist such as [[G.Soul]], Groovyroom, Woogie, Sik-K, pH-1, Avatar Darko, Phe R.E.D.S, Raz Simone, and Jarv Dee.\n\nOn July 20, 2018, Park released the EP ''Ask Bout Me'', which features seven tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.47732/title.jay-park-reveals-tracklist-for-ask-bout-me-ep-featuring-2-chainz-vic-mensa|title=Jay Park \"Ask Bout Me\" EP Stream, Cover Art & Tracklist|work=HipHopDX|last=Eustice|first=Kyle|date=July 19, 2018|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Jay Park released a collaborative EP with American producer [[Hit-Boy]], called ''This Wasn't Supposed to Happen'' and named after the surprise nature of their collaboration. ''This Wasn't Supposed to Happen'' marked Park's second release under Roc Nation, and was preceded by their single \"K-Town\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8543095/jay-park-hit-boy-this-wasnt-supposed-to-happen-ep-announce-k-town|title='This Wasn't Supposed to Happen': Jay Park & Hit-Boy Announce Surprise EP: Exclusive|work=Billboard|date=November 8, 2019|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref> In the month after, Park collabed with Latin artist and fellow Roc Nation signee [[Mozart La Para]] for the single \"Son Malas\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://larepublica.pe/cultura-asiatica/2019/12/21/jay-park-y-mozart-la-para-son-malas-primera-colaboracion-de-rapero-park-jaebeom-con-un-artista-latino-kpop-youtube-video/|title=Jay Park lanza \"Son malas\" junto a cantante dominicano Mozart La Para|work=La Republica|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref> Both singles contained music videos.\n\n==Artistry==\n===Influences===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Usherraymond (300dpi).jpg\n| width1 = 100\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 =\n| image2 = Michael Jackson 1984.jpg\n| width2 = 100\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 =\n| footer = [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]] (''left'') and [[Michael Jackson]] (''right'') are two of Park's biggest influences\n}}\nPark's music takes its roots in [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], more specifically from the 90s.<ref>{{cite web |title = \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 \"\ud798\ub4e0 \uac74 \uc601\uc6d0\ud55c \uac8c \uc544\ub2c8\ub2c8\uae4c \uc798 \uacac\ub514\uba74 \ub41c\ub2e4\uace0 \uc0dd\uac01\ud574\uc694\" (Jay Park: \"Because hardship does not last forever, I can endure it.\") |author = Gang, Myeong-seok |url = http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?sec=news13&a_id=2011051822185869408 |publisher = 10Asia |date = May 19, 2012 |accessdate = September 9, 2012 |language = ko |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110523011959/http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?sec=news13&a_id=2011051822185869408 |archive-date = May 23, 2011 |url-status = dead }}</ref> He is influenced by the work of American artists he grew up listening to, such as [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Ne-Yo]], [[Chris Brown (American entertainer)|Chris Brown]], [[Ginuwine]], [[Musiq Soulchild]], [[Justin Timberlake]], [[Eminem]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Nas]], [[Tupac]], [[Dr. Dre]], and [[Canibus]].<ref name=\"complex\" /><ref name=\"neyo\" /><ref name=\"mj\">{{cite web| title=Park Jae-beom - Part 2| url=http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?sec=ent0&a_id=2010080918535126395| author=Kang, Myoung-Seok| publisher=10Asia| date=August 9, 2010| accessdate=September 9, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610215209/http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?sec=ent0&a_id=2010080918535126395| archive-date=June 10, 2015| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"chrisbrown\">{{cite web |title=Jay Park says, \"My music lacks mass appeal? Please open up to me\" (Interview) |url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stviewEng.php?type=3&no=2012020908205184470 |publisher=StarNews |author=Park, Young Woong |date=February 10, 2012 |accessdate=September 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610204613/http://star.mt.co.kr/stviewEng.php?type=3&no=2012020908205184470 |archivedate=June 10, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"influence\">{{cite web|title=Jay Park joins Facebook! | url=http://www.allkpop.com/2010/09/jay-park-joins-facebook|publisher=allkpop|date = September 18, 2010 | accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> Park credits Usher as his idol and as one of his biggest influences, who he started listening to in the 6th grade.<ref name=\"usher\">{{cite web|title=Jay Park fools around with two new covers on Youtube | url=http://www.allkpop.com/2010/05/jay-park-fools-around-with-new-usher-cover-on-youtube|publisher=allkpop|date = May 4, 2010 | accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"entermedia\">{{cite web|title=\uac00\uc2dd\uacfc\ub294 \ubb34\uad00\ud55c 26\uc0b4 \uccad\ub144 \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 (The 26-year-old Jay Park is irrelevant to pretense) | url=http://entermedia.co.kr/news/news_view.html?idx=1212|publisher=Entermedia|author=Jung, Suk-hee|date = March 20, 2012 | accessdate=September 9, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> He also cites Michael Jackson as his role model, as \"he is the best\".<ref name=\"mj\" /> He cites both Usher and Michael Jackson as singers and dancers who influence him vocally and in dance, as he attempts to mimic them, looking at their music videos.<ref name=\"entermedia\" /> Park also cites Chris Brown as an inspiration, and wants \"to be a singer who can be good at both singing and rapping like [him]\".<ref name=\"chrisbrown\" /> Park began listening to hip hop music when he was in second grade, after one of his cousins let him listen to [[Warren G]]'s \"[[Regulate (song)|Regulate]]\".<ref name=\"complex\" /><ref>{{cite web| title=Jay Park - A Walk In The Park| url=http://www.yoraps.com/next2blow1.php?subaction=showfull&id=1298390862&archive=&start_from=&ucat=4&| publisher=YoRaps.com| author=Jai Boo| date=February 22, 2011| accessdate=September 9, 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226135746/http://www.yoraps.com/next2blow1.php?subaction=showfull&id=1298390862&archive=&start_from=&ucat=4&| archivedate=February 26, 2011}}</ref> In general, Park stated he \"doesn't really listen to music to get inspiration, I listen to music because I listen to music, but I do get inspired when I listen to music, it definitely helps\".<ref name=singapore-press-conference-2013>{{cite web|title=Jay Park - Live in Singapore 2013 Press Conference Part 1|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VEOucNGIyyw|publisher=imaginetvnetwork|accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFor his dance, Park highlights [[Art of Movement]], Skill Methods, and [[Massive Monkees]] as b-boy crews that influence him.<ref name=\"influence\" /><ref name=\"dance\">{{cite news| title=Jay Park: Second Shot at Fame Overwhelming| url=http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/280126/jay-park-second-shot-fame-overwhelming| author=Hicap, Jonathan M.| newspaper=Manila Bulletin| date=October 2, 2010| accessdate=September 9, 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101005034850/http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/280126/jay-park-second-shot-fame-overwhelming| archivedate=October 5, 2010}}</ref> He also cites Andrew Baterina from [[SoReal Cru]]; Movement Lifestyle's members Keone Madrid, Lyle Beniga, and [[Shaun Evaristo]]; Ian Eastwood; and Twitch.<ref name=\"influence\" /><ref name=\"dance\" /> Park is also inspired by Taiwanese-American NBA player [[Jeremy Lin]], saying that Lin \"was off the radar and now he's playing with the best of the best. People can't hate on him even though they want to because he's so good. That's how a K-pop star has to be over in America if they want to succeed. They have to be so good in every single way that even if people hate, they can't really say anything\".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=How Jay Park Became the Face of a 'New Breed' of K-Pop R&B | url=http://www.spin.com/blogs/how-jay-park-became-face-new-breed-k-pop-rb|author=Bevan, David|magazine = SPIN Magazine|date = March 9, 2012 | accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Musical style===\nJay Park's music is generally [[contemporary R&B]] and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], but he also incorporates [[Pop music|pop]], [[Dance music|dance]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[Electronic music|electronic]] and [[Acoustic music|acoustic]] into his songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park: A Breath of Fresh Air | url=http://theurbanwire.com/2012/07/23/jay-park/|publisher=The Urban Wire|author= Chan, Genevieve| date = July 23, 2012 | accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> Prior to debuting with 2PM, Park was coached vocally by former SOLID member and renowned R&B artist [[Kim Jo-han]], also known to be the vocal coach of many idols in the industry.<ref name=\"johan\">{{cite web|title=Jay Park & his past mentor Kim Jo Han talk about their relationship | url=http://www.allkpop.com/2011/11/jay-park-his-past-mentor-kim-jo-han-talk-about-their-relationship|publisher=allkpop|date = November 22, 2011 | accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kim Jo Han: Vocal Trainer For SNSD, 2PM, and Super Junior | url=http://www.soompi.com/2011/07/25/kim-jo-han-vocal-trainer-for-snsd-2pm-and-super-junior/|date = July 25, 2011 | accessdate=September 9, 2012}}</ref> Kim went on to say that \"[Park] has an appealing and unique voice\" and \"definitely stood out amongst the rest\".<ref name=\"johan\" /> Park began to write rap lyrics in eighth grade.<ref name=\"10asia\">{{cite web| title=Jay Park - Pt. 1| url=http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?a_id=2012022813443173203| publisher=10Asia| author=Choi, Ji-eun| date=February 28, 2012| accessdate=September 9, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127124454/http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?a_id=2012022813443173203| archive-date=January 27, 2016| url-status=dead}}</ref> Since becoming a solo artist, he has complete creative control over his music : he writes and composes his own songs, produces his albums, chooses the people he wants to work with, and participates in the mastering and mixing of his songs, something almost unheard-of for a singer in the Korean music industry.<ref name=\"complex\" /><ref name=\"10asia\" /><ref name=\"sound\">{{cite web| title=Jay Park: \u2032I Want to Become a First Place Musician\u2032| url=http://enewsworld.mnet.com/kcelebs/kcelebs_detail.asp?stID=218| publisher=CJ E&M enewsWorld| author=Kim, Ji-yeon| date=February 24, 2012| accessdate=September 9, 2012| archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129001222/http://enewsworld.mnet.com/kcelebs/kcelebs_detail.asp?stID=218| archive-date=January 29, 2013| url-status=dead}}</ref> More than making hit songs, Park says he wants people to hear to his style of music, to make them listen to \"Jay Park-sounding\" music.<ref name=\"sound\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 \"\ube44\uc988\ub2c8\uc2a4 \ub0c4\uc0c8\ub098\ub294 \uc74c\uc545 \ubcc4\ub85c, \ub3c8 \uad00\uc2ec\uc5c6\ub2e4\" (Jay Park is \"Not interested in doing music just for the business and money\") | url=http://m.media.daum.net/entertain/enews/view?newsid=20120213082510586|publisher=NewsEn|author=Jun Won|date = February 13, 2012 | accessdate=September 9, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Being fluent in both English and Korean, Park writes songs in these two languages.<ref name=\"video\" /> He admits that he is more at ease when writing songs in English than in Korean, as he started learning Korean in his late teens.<ref name=\"10asia\" /> Having grown up listening to music of American artists, he admits his music sounds more \"American\" than K-Pop, saying it is the style of music he wants to make, while still being recognized as K-Pop.<ref>{{cite web | title = Interview: Jay Park scores big after a 'turbulent couple of years' | author = Cha, Frances | publisher = CNN GO | date = June 3, 2011 | url = http://www.cnngo.com/seoul/life/interview-jay-park-scores-big-after-turbulent-years-050318 | accessdate = September 9, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919010253/http://www.cnngo.com/seoul/life/interview-jay-park-scores-big-after-turbulent-years-050318 | archive-date = September 19, 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\uc2a4\ubb3c \ub2e4\uc12f \uccad\ub144 \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94\uc758 \uc774\uc911\uc131 (The duality of the 25-year-old Jay Park) | url=http://star.mk.co.kr/new/view.php?mc=ST&no=106996&year=2012|publisher=Star MK|author=Lee, Hyun-woo|date = February 17, 2012 | accessdate=September 9, 2012|language=ko}}</ref><ref name=\"urbanwire\">{{cite news| title =How Jay Park took Manila by storm (literally) | author =Ignacio, Angela V. | newspaper =Philippine Daily Inquirer| date = May 12, 2012 |url =http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/47431/how-jay-park-took-manila-by-storm-literally | accessdate = September 9, 2012}}</ref> His musical process starts by listening to a lot of beats sent by various producers, while thinking of what kind of song he wants to write, and eventually short-listing a selection of potential beats to work with.<ref name=\"10asia\" /> Then, Park works on the melody of the song, along with ideas and lyrics. He writes the hook of the song first, and finally the verses.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Beginnings |author=Virina, Bianca |publisher=iammeg.ph |url=http://www.iammeg.ph/news/new-beginnings |accessdate=September 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521192428/http://www.iammeg.ph/news/new-beginnings |archivedate=May 21, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title =Jay Park embraced by Filipinos | author =Esteves, Patricia | publisher =philstar.com | date =May 6, 2012 | url =http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?publicationSubCategoryId=70&articleId=804146 | archive-url =https://archive.today/20130208163112/http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?publicationSubCategoryId=70&articleId=804146 | url-status =dead | archive-date =February 8, 2013 | accessdate =September 9, 2012 }}</ref> Park is inspired by everything when writing songs: \"just listening to good songs, seeing a good live performance, having good conversations with people. Just everyday life\".<ref name=\"urbanwire\" /> Some songs Park wrote are influenced by songs from other artists, for example, his song \"Turn Off Your Phone\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|\uc804\ud654\uae30\ub97c \uaebc\ub194}}; Revised Romanization: ''Jeonhwagireur Kkeonwa'') from his album ''New Breed'' was inspired by [[Leessang]]'s hit single \"Turn Off the TV ...\" (Korean: {{lang|ko|TV\ub97c \uaed0\ub124\u2026}}; Revised Romanization: ''TV Reurkkeotne'') from their 7th album ''Asura Balbalta''.<ref name=\"10asia\" />\n\n==Endorsements==\nIn July 2010, Park was announced to be endorsing [[Levi Strauss & Co.]]'s new brand, dENiZEN. He had previously revealed on YouTube in June 2010, before coming back to Korea, that he was at a photoshoot without revealing it was for dENiZEN.<ref>{{cite web| title =\uc7ac\ubc94 \uccad\ubc14\uc9c0 \uad11\uace0 \ucd2c\uc601...\uc601\ud654\uc5d0 \ub178\ub798\uc5d0 CF\uae4c\uc9c0 \uc798\ub098\uac00\ub124~ (Jaebeom shoots an advertisement for jeans... with a movie, songs and now a CF, he's doing well~) | author =Park, Geon-ug | publisher =Nate| date = July 19, 2010 |url =http://www.gwangnam.co.kr/news/news_view.htm?idxno=2010071917542686359 | accessdate = June 6, 2012|language=ko}}{{dead link|date=December 2012}}</ref> He continued to endorse the brand until the end of 2011 with female model [[Kwon Ri-sae]].<ref>{{cite web | title =\ub370\ub2c8\uc98c, \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 \uad8c\ub9ac\uc138\uc758 \uc720\ucf8c\ud55c \uaca8\uc6b8 \ud654\ubcf4 \uacf5\uac1c (Denizen reveals their pleasant Winter photoshoot with Park Jaebeom and Kwon Rise) | author =Park, Geon-ug | publisher =Hankyung | date =November 10, 2011 | url =http://kmomnews.hankyung.com/news/apps/news.sub_view?popup=0&nid=05&c1=05&c2=05&c3=00&nkey=201111101517271 | accessdate =June 6, 2012 | language =ko | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20130124232802/http://kmomnews.hankyung.com/news/apps/news.sub_view?popup=0&nid=05&c1=05&c2=05&c3=00&nkey=201111101517271 | archivedate =January 24, 2013 }}</ref> Park and Kwon recorded a remix duet song of dENiZEN's theme song, \"Manifesto\".<ref>{{cite web | title =\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94-\uad8c\ub9ac\uc138, \ucee4\ud50c\ud654\ubcf4 \uc774\uc5b4 \ucee4\ud50c\uc1a1 \uacf5\uac1c '\ub450\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud638\ud761' (Park Jaebeom and Kwon Rise releases a couple song after their couple photoshoot: 'second time working together') | author =Jeon, Ah-ram | publisher =TV Daily | date =August 26, 2011 | url =http://tvdaily.mk.co.kr/read.php3?aid=1314319854195283003 | accessdate =June 6, 2012 | language =ko | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20130218200935/http://tvdaily.mk.co.kr/read.php3?aid=1314319854195283003 | archivedate =February 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2012, Park was chosen by [[KT Tech]] to be the official model of Take HD, a new smartphone by the brand.<ref>{{cite web| title =KT '\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94\ud3f0' \ud14c\uc774\ud06cHD \ucd9c\uc2dc\u2026\uc6d454 \uac00\uc785\uc2dc 16\ub9cc\uc6d0\ub300 (KT releases TakeHD, the \"Jay Park Phone\") | author =Kwon, Min-kyung | publisher =Korean Economy via Nate| date = January 3, 2012 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20120103n06615 | accessdate = June 6, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> Park released the maxi-single \"Take HD Special Maxi Album\" on February 7, 2012, produced by KT Tech to promote the smartphone.<ref>{{cite web| title =KT\ud14c\ud06c, \ud14c\uc774\ud06cHD \ucd9c\uc2dc \uae30\ub150 \ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94 \uc2f1\uae00\uc568\ubc94 \uc81c\uc791 (KT Tech to produce Jay Park's single album) | author = Kwon, Young-jun | publisher =Nate | date = January 10, 2012 |url =http://news.nate.com/view/20120110n06919 | accessdate = January 10, 2012|language=ko}}</ref> The maxi-single includes remixes of Park's lead single from his album ''[[New Breed (Jay Park album)|New Breed]]'', \"Know Your Name\", released on the same day.\n\nPark appears with fellow SidusHQ celebrities [[Jang Hyuk]], [[Kim Su-ro]], Kim Shin-young and Jang Hee-jin in the [[MMORPG]] ''[[Lineage 2]]'' as supporting characters.<ref>{{cite web | title ='\ub9ac\ub2c8\uc9c02' \uc5d0 '\ubc15\uc7ac\ubc94' \uacfc '\uc7a5\ud601' \uc774 \ub5b4\ub2e4? ('Lineage 2' Park Jaebeom and Jang Hyuk shows up?) | publisher =Xportsnews | date =February 8, 2012 | url =http://xportsnews.hankyung.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=214808 | accessdate =June 26, 2012 | language =ko | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20130208093818/http://xportsnews.hankyung.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=214808 | archivedate =February 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn behalf of [[Naver]]'s first \"Fashion Collaboration\" event, Park also with fashion designer 275C for creation of a joint T-shirt titled ''Live Free'', representing Park's free mind and lifestyle, and displaying both the [[Space Needle]] from Seattle, his hometown, and the [[Namsan Tower]] from [[Seoul]], where he currently lives. The back of the T-shirt shows the names of his b-boy crews [[Art of Movement]] and Korean Assassins, and dance collaboration team, Project Prepix Asia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fashion Icon Collaboration, Jay Park T-Shirt 'Live Free' Revealed |publisher=Jay Park official website |date=May 30, 2012 |url=http://jaypark.com/news/?p=442 |accessdate=June 26, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nPark was also chosen to endorse and model for casual clothing brand [[:ko:\uad6c\uae40\uc2a4 \ucef4\ud37c\ub2c8|Googims]] for their 2012 collections; after the announcement was made, it was stated that \"the brand's home page server was down every five minutes\".<ref>{{cite web | title =Jay Park's Summer Spread Shuts Down Server | author =Billboard Korea | publisher =Billboard Korea | date =January 10, 2012 | url =http://www.billboard.co.kr/v1/news_view.html?i=28077&t=405#.T82ZakPYA8H.twitter | archive-date =February 18, 2013 | archive-url =https://archive.today/20130218204335/http://www.billboard.co.kr/v1/news_view.html?i=28077&t=405%23.T82ZakPYA8H.twitter | url-status =dead| accessdate =June 6, 2012 }}</ref> A behind the scenes video of Park performing an impromptu dance to \"[[Gangnam Style]]\" by [[Psy (rapper)|Psy]] at a Googims photo shoot was uploaded to YouTube on September 2, 2012, capturing the public's attention for his unique take of the choreography.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay Park Goes \"Gangnam Style\" on Set of New Googims CF!|url=http://www.soompi.com/2012/09/03/jay-park-goes-gangnam-style-on-set-of-new-cf/|publisher=Soompi|accessdate=September 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=korea-dot-com-gangnam-style>{{cite web|title=Jay Park upgrades \"Gangnam Style\" choreography|url=http://en.korea.com/blog/enter/k-pop/jay-park-makes-choreography-from-gangnam-style-more-powerful/|accessdate=September 5, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130127092441/http://en.korea.com/blog/enter/k-pop/jay-park-makes-choreography-from-gangnam-style-more-powerful/|archivedate=January 27, 2013}}</ref> Park also has been selected as the new model for outdoor clothing brand, Williamsburg, participating in TV commercials and fan-signing events.<ref>{{cite web | title = Jay Park Models for Outdoors Wear Brand, Williamsburg | author = Ho, Stewart | publisher = Mnet | date = June 20, 2012 | url = http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201206201604_8262&META=5&ID=201206201604_8262 | accessdate = June 21, 2012 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130129052247/http://global.mnet.com/news/newsdetail.m?searchNewsVO.news_id=201206201604_8262&META=5&ID=201206201604_8262 | archive-date = January 29, 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Park, a long time fan of [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], participated at a Nike event in [[Seoul]], [[Korea]], titled \"Nike on Air\", which was streamed live online via [[Ustream]].\n\nIn 2016, Park, alongside [[Jessica Jung]], Tian Yo, Charlene, and [[Pakho Chau]] modelled for Adidas's Celebration of Sportswear campaign.  In March 2016, Park modelled for [[Umbro|Umbro Korea]]'s 'Reborn to Heritage' campaign; and did a photoshoot for [[Police (brand)|Police Sunglasses]], which was featured in the April issue of [[Dazed|Dazed Korea]] magazine.\n\n== Personal life ==\nOn March 8, 2020, a police report was filed against [[Brian Ortega]] for alleged slapping Park who serves as the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) featherweight fighter [[Chan Sung Jung]]'s (Korean Zombie) translator and a good friend of Jung while Jung went to the bathroom at [[UFC 248]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/korean-zombie-chan-sung-jung-manager-police-report-brian-ortega-slap-ufc-248|title=Chan Sung Jung manager: Police report filed after alleged Brian Ortega slap at UFC 248|date=March 8, 2020|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2020/3/8/21170277/brian-ortega-thrown-out-of-ufc-248-after-slapping-k-pop-star-and-korean-zombie-translator-jay-park|title=Brian Ortega thrown out of UFC 248 after slapping K-Pop star Jay Park|last=Harkness|first=Ryan|date=March 8, 2020|website=MMAmania.com|language=en|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Jay Park discography}}\n<!-- Per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians/Article guidelines]], The discography section of the musician's primary article should \"provide a summary of the musician's major works.\" -->\n* ''[[New Breed (Jay Park album)|New Breed]]'' (2012) [Korean]\n* ''Evolution'' (2014) [Korean]\n* ''Worldwide'' (2015) [Korean]\n* ''Everything You Wanted'' (2016) [Korean]\n* ''The Road Less Traveled'' (2019) [English]\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Jay Park videography}}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Program\n!Network\n!Notes\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Immortal Songs: Singing the Legend|Immortal Songs 2]]''\n|[[KBS2]]\n|Regular cast member\n|-\n| 2012\n|''True Man Show''\n|[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|Episodes 1-11\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n|''[[Dancing 9]] (Season 2)''\n|[[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]\n|Judge, Blue Eye Team\n|-\n|''[[Saturday Night Live Korea]]''\n|[[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n|Joined as permanent cast member\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\n|''[[America's Next Top Model (cycle 21)]]''\n|[[The CW]]\n|Guest\n|-\n|''[[Show Me the Money (South Korean TV series)|Show Me The Money 4]]''\n|rowspan=2|[[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]\n|Judge/Producer with [[Loco (rapper)|Loco]]\n|-\n| 2015\n|''[[Unpretty Rapstar 2]]''\n|Producer team with [[Cha Cha Malone]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016\n|''[[Saturday Night Live Korea]]''\n|[[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n|AOMG special\n|-\n|''[[King of Mask Singer]]''\n|[[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|Episode 41 & 42 (\"Cold City Monkey\")\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2017\n|[[Show Me the Money (South Korean TV series)|''Show Me The Money 6'']]\n|[[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]\n|Judge/Producer with [[Dok2]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|''[[Asia's Got Talent]]''\n|rowspan=2|[[AXN Asia]]\n|Judge, [[Asia's Got Talent (season 2)|Season 2]]\n|-\n|2019\n|Judge, [[Asia's Got Talent (season 3)|Season 3]]\n|}\n\n==Tours and concerts==\n'''Headlining'''\n* White Love Party Concert (2010)\n* New Breed Live in Seoul (2012)\n* [[APAHM]] Tour (2012)\n* [[MTV World Stage Live in Malaysia]] (2012)\n* New Breed Asia Tour (2012)\n* Australia Tour (2012)\n* Jay Park First European Tour (2013)\n* Jay park I like 2 party in BKK (2013)\n* AOMG 2014 USA TOUR (2014)\n* Show Me The Money 4 Concert Tour (2015)\n* AOMG \"Follow The Movement\" \u2013 Korea & U.S. Concert Tours (2016)\n* AOMG Concert 2017 \u2018Follow The Movement\u2019\n* Jay Park - All Of Me (Korean Concert) (2018)\n* [[Sexy 4eva World Tour|SEXY 4EVA World Tour]] (2019)\n\n'''Supporting'''\n* [[Ne-Yo]] Live in Seoul (2011)\n* [[Korean Music Festival]] (2011)\n* [[South by Southwest]] (2014)\n* South by Southwest (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n<big>'''[[Mnet Asian Music Awards]]'''</big>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! width=5%|Year\n! style=\"width:40%;\" | Recipient\n! style=\"width:45%;\"| Award\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Result\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Ref.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[2011 Mnet Asian Music Awards|2011]]\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Abandoned (song)|\"Abandoned\"]]\n|align=\"center\" |Best Dance Performance \u2013 Solo\n|{{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 MAMA Winners|url=http://mama.interest.me/2014mama/history?type=winner&year=2011|website=Mnet Asian Music Awards|publisher=CJ E&M|accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mnet Releases MAMA Awards Nominees' List|url=http://www.soompi.com/2011/11/01/mnet-releases-mama-awards-nominees-list/|website=Soompi|accessdate=December 15, 2014|date=November 1, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |[[Mnet Asian Music Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[2013 Mnet Asian Music Awards|2013]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[Joah (song)|\"Joah\"]]\n|align=\"center\" |[[Mnet Asian Music Award for Best Dance Performance|Best Dance Performance - Male Solo]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=2013_nom>{{cite web|title=2013 Mnet Asian Music Awards (part 1)|url=http://mwave.interest.me/mnettv/videodetail.m?searchVideoDetailVO.clip_id=158970|website=Mwave|publisher=MAMA|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[2015 Mnet Asian Music Awards|2015]]\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| \"Mommae\"\n|align=\"center\"|[[Mnet Asian Music Awa